{"term":"1957","caseName":"Reeves v. Alabama","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1957/66","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - January 08, 1958","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13361","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 66, Jeremiah Reeves, Jr.versus State of Alabama.","start":0,"stop":25.314,"duration":25.31},{"text":"Mr. Hall.","start":25.314,"stop":27.053,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":27.053,"stop":34.236,"duration":7.18},{"text":"Our argument would be a divided one.","start":34.236,"stop":38.926,"duration":4.69},{"text":"I will make a few of this statement, my colleague Mr. Billingsley will speak in rebuttal.","start":38.926,"stop":48.922,"duration":10},{"text":"This particular case is here in this Court the second time.","start":48.922,"stop":55.159,"duration":6.24},{"text":"Some time ago, back in 1952, petitioner, a young Negro boy, age 16, is arrested in Montgomery, Alabama and was held three to four days in jail and imprisoned (Inaudible) question.","start":55.159,"stop":89.766,"duration":34.61},{"text":"After that time, he was then indicted.On the next day, he was arraigned, charged with rape and subsequent to that, two days later he was tried, convicted of the crime of rape sentenced to the electric chair.On that occasion back in 1952, his counsel was (Inaudible), I believe.","start":89.766,"stop":119.098,"duration":29.33},{"text":"I don't recall exactly what their exact name but he did not have the same counsel as now.","start":119.098,"stop":127.965,"duration":8.87},{"text":"On the day of the arraignment -- I beg your pardon.He was arrested on November 10.","start":127.965,"stop":139.446,"duration":11.48},{"text":"He was indicted on November 14th, 1952.","start":139.446,"stop":143.194,"duration":3.75},{"text":"Now, from the 10th to the 14th of November, he was kept incommunicado in the City Jail of Montgomery and at Kilby Prison.","start":143.194,"stop":153.548,"duration":10.35},{"text":"He was not allowed to talk with his parents or to have counsel or have been into the counsel.On the 14th of November, he was indicted by grand jury of Montgomery -- in Montgomery County Alabama.","start":153.548,"stop":169.137,"duration":15.59},{"text":"Now, on the very next day, on November 15th, he was arraigned some time between November 15 -- November 14th and November 15th term of arraignment, counsel wasn't good for him.","start":169.137,"stop":184.333,"duration":15.2},{"text":"On the arraignment, his then counsel asked for a continuance in order to (Inaudible) which request was abused.","start":184.333,"stop":197.686,"duration":13.35},{"text":"Subsequently, on the 17th of November 1952, after arraignment, he was shared with the copy of the indictment and a list of the merit which has been drawn especially on the day of arraignment.","start":197.686,"stop":212.529,"duration":14.84},{"text":"On the trial of the cause, his counsel sought to withdraw pleas, end it on arraignment, pleas to demerits in order that he might attack the indictment on constitutional grounds.","start":212.529,"stop":227.802,"duration":15.27},{"text":"That request was overruled.","start":227.802,"stop":230.867,"duration":3.06},{"text":"All of this is supplied at the record.","start":230.867,"stop":232.39,"duration":1.52},{"text":"It appears in the record.","start":232.39,"stop":235.522,"duration":3.13},{"text":"The trial then went ahead to a conclusion at which time Reeves is convicted as I've said before of rape.","start":235.522,"stop":244.779,"duration":9.26},{"text":"This decision was affirmed by the Alabama Supreme Court.","start":244.779,"stop":249.354,"duration":4.58},{"text":"Subsequently, this Court granted certiorari and after a hearing, the Alabama Court which has raised a reversal which is without directions, Kennedy against Alabama and (Inaudible) against Alabama was cited, subsequently, the State of Alabama against Jeremiah Reeves.","start":249.354,"stop":280.231,"duration":30.88},{"text":"There's no trial in 1955.","start":280.231,"stop":288.046,"duration":7.81},{"text":"On this particular trial, there is no reindictment of the arraignment.","start":288.046,"stop":295.294,"duration":7.25},{"text":"Counsel for the defendant on the petitioner at that time again moved the Court -- moved the Court for permission to withdraw please in it on his previous arraignment in 1952 for the purpose of attack, the validity of this indictment on federal constitutional grounds.","start":295.294,"stop":316.031,"duration":20.74},{"text":"We have specifically two grounds which we desire to explore.","start":316.031,"stop":322.867,"duration":6.84},{"text":"One was the fact that under the reversal of this Honorable Court in the previous case, in the citation of the two cases, Kennedy against Alabama and Vermont against Alabama.","start":322.867,"stop":334.622,"duration":11.75},{"text":"It was our conclusion that certain culprit statements and confessions introduced on the previous trial could not that -- that because of those culprit statements and those confessions, the conviction could not stand and it was our conviction and our argument and the effort to attack the indictment this time, that the only thing before the grand jury that indicted Reeves was in fact the statements and the confessions which had been thrown out and without this, the indictment could not stand.","start":334.622,"stop":377.414,"duration":42.79},{"text":"Secondly, it was on the confession that the grand jury, which indicted petitioner contained absolutely no Negroes and that the system of the State of Alabama of throwing members of such grand jury said at that time was designed to exclude members or to discriminate against them by reason of their race and color then tried to the provisions of the federal constitution.","start":377.414,"stop":407.718,"duration":30.3},{"text":"The trial court without a hearing overruled our motions.","start":407.718,"stop":415.864,"duration":8.15},{"text":"We then filed a motion to strike within our drawn to hear this particular case because of exclusion of Negroes from the juries in Alabama.","start":415.864,"stop":428.585,"duration":12.72},{"text":"The trial court set this motion down for a hearing and on the hearing, it appeared that the Commissioners, the Jury Commissioners of Montgomery County at a system of selecting persons for the jury absolutely contrary to the system laid down by the Alabama court and the testimony in fact of the Commissioners showed that they had very little system indeed for the selection of Negroes, although they contended that there was no discrimination.","start":428.585,"stop":469.487,"duration":40.9},{"text":"Judge Eugene Carter, the Circuit judge of the County who testified that he -- members of the Board of Jury Commissioners had been for 27 years -- some years said that his method was to interview some Negroes whom he knew, who suggested names for the -- for the panel.","start":469.487,"stop":494.955,"duration":25.47},{"text":"But as to identify anyone of such persons, he refused because he said it might embarrass him.","start":494.955,"stop":502.312,"duration":7.36},{"text":"We asked him to identify anyone particular Negro who might be on the panel jury there at Montgomery County.","start":502.312,"stop":509.774,"duration":7.46},{"text":"He refused to do that.","start":509.774,"stop":512.457,"duration":2.68},{"text":"He also testified that he had drawn the grand jury in Montgomery County for the past 21 years that he remembered one Negro and he said on a grand jury, but could not remember as many as two during that period.","start":512.457,"stop":531.376,"duration":18.92},{"text":"I also testified that up until the past one or two years, it had been very difficult to get Negroes for service on the jury and that up until the past one or two years, very few Negroes had served.","start":531.376,"stop":548.708,"duration":17.33},{"text":"Judge Eugene Jones, the Circuit Clerk, Mr. Mathews who also served on the Jury Commission, both testified similarly.","start":548.708,"stop":559.161,"duration":10.45},{"text":"Their methods of selecting Negroes at the same manner through personal acquaintance by contact of various clubs and organizations, but none of them could designate or would designate a particular club or organization except for the NAACP and the local (Inaudible).","start":559.161,"stop":583.957,"duration":24.8},{"text":"Nor could we get from any of them, particular names of individuals that they knew to be on the jury role of Montgomery County are listed on the jury courts of that County.","start":583.957,"stop":597.761,"duration":13.8},{"text":"Incidentally, we ask the Court for permission to have the jury role examined by any of these particular witnesses for the purpose of ascertaining whether or no any particular name on such role could be identified by these witnesses who was certainly on a position to know as Negroes.","start":597.761,"stop":621.694,"duration":23.93},{"text":"The Court --","start":621.694,"stop":623.048,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":623.048,"stop":629.288,"duration":6.24}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice, we do not know.","start":629.288,"stop":631.418,"duration":2.13},{"text":"We asked the Circuit Court Clerk who was also the clerk of the Jury Commission and as to what the size of the -- the jury panel was or the role.","start":631.418,"stop":644.193,"duration":12.77},{"text":"You mean the entire role?","start":644.193,"stop":645.776,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what -- what's your practice?","start":645.776,"stop":647.411,"duration":1.63},{"text":"Does the Court draw a panel to serve for a week or two or something like that?","start":647.411,"stop":653.145,"duration":5.73}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I beg your pardon.I think I misunderstood you.","start":653.145,"stop":656.209,"duration":3.06},{"text":"The panel is usually (Inaudible) of the trial of any -- of any one term.","start":656.209,"stop":662.541,"duration":6.33}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And when you tell us that Judge Carter, did you say?","start":662.541,"stop":666.569,"duration":4.03},{"text":"Testified --","start":666.569,"stop":666.919,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":666.919,"stop":667.242,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that he could remember not more than one Negro ever serving on the panel, do you mean on a panel of a hundred?","start":667.242,"stop":673.523,"duration":6.28}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":673.523,"stop":676.304,"duration":2.78},{"text":"Perhaps, I should -- allow me to try to explain this, the panel -- the jury panel drawn for service for a term is around a hundred persons.","start":676.304,"stop":686.095,"duration":9.79},{"text":"A hundred persons is enough.","start":686.095,"stop":688.48,"duration":2.38},{"text":"The number of persons who served on a grand jury is 18 persons.","start":688.48,"stop":692.62,"duration":4.14},{"text":"Now, out of the panel of a hundred, they draw -- they draw petty juries and a grand jury.","start":692.62,"stop":698.689,"duration":6.07},{"text":"Now, from this panel of 100 persons, Judge Carter, who draws most of this -- of the grand juries will then take these 100 names, put them in their hat.","start":698.689,"stop":709.021,"duration":10.33},{"text":"They throw them through the hat and draw from that hat 18 new service grand jurors.","start":709.021,"stop":713.973,"duration":4.95}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And he does that once a year?","start":713.973,"stop":715.367,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"He does that twice a year.","start":715.367,"stop":716.702,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Twice a year.","start":716.702,"stop":717.628,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":717.628,"stop":718.158,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now -- and I don't quite get the significance of the one Negro.","start":718.158,"stop":723.086,"duration":4.93}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Over a period of 21 years that he has enjoined such grand juries in Montgomery County, Alabama, he remembered one Negro having served on a grand jury.","start":723.086,"stop":733.493,"duration":10.41}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That is only one --","start":733.493,"stop":734.694,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Only one --","start":734.694,"stop":735.041,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in all the number of panels of a hundred --","start":735.041,"stop":735.526,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in 21 years.","start":735.526,"stop":736.547,"duration":1.02},{"text":"That was his testimony.","start":736.547,"stop":739.112,"duration":2.56}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"There was a -- there was a hearing on this?","start":739.112,"stop":740.907,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":740.907,"stop":741.717,"duration":0.81},{"text":"It was the hearing not on the motion to push the indictment Mr. Justice, but the hearing on the motion to question the jury drawn to hear this particular case.That is where this testimony came up.","start":741.717,"stop":756.906,"duration":15.19}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Did -- did the judge remember what year that was over the last 20 years?","start":756.906,"stop":759.254,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":759.254,"stop":759.625,"duration":0.37},{"text":"He didn't.","start":759.625,"stop":760.261,"duration":0.64},{"text":"I don't recall it.","start":760.261,"stop":761.979,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Don't bother to tell.","start":761.979,"stop":763.578,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought the reference showed (Inaudible).","start":763.578,"stop":767.79,"duration":4.21}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":767.79,"stop":768.088,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"There were eight Negroes on the County and agreed on -- on the aide of the matter.","start":768.088,"stop":777.504,"duration":9.42}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":777.504,"stop":777.818,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Three on the panel that tried this case.","start":777.818,"stop":780.149,"duration":2.33}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"That is true, Your Honor.","start":780.149,"stop":782.981,"duration":2.83},{"text":"That is true but this was the petty jury.","start":782.981,"stop":787.17,"duration":4.19},{"text":"Now there had been.","start":787.17,"stop":788.112,"duration":0.94},{"text":"There was testimony from the bar.","start":788.112,"stop":790.083,"duration":1.97},{"text":"We questioned the members of the Bar of Montgomery County, several of them and that was a considerable testimony to the extent that several Negroes had been on jury panels in previous years.","start":790.083,"stop":803.442,"duration":13.36},{"text":"But to have Negroes actually serve on juries was another thing.","start":803.442,"stop":809.564,"duration":6.12},{"text":"That was the testimony.There were eight on this panel of 100 persons.","start":809.564,"stop":815.311,"duration":5.75},{"text":"I have -- none served on this jury and none served on the grand jury which indicted it.","start":815.311,"stop":821.083,"duration":5.77}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"They were not been served on this jury --","start":821.083,"stop":823.829,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":823.829,"stop":823.987,"duration":0.16}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"But they were called to serve on --","start":823.987,"stop":825.528,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"They were called --","start":825.528,"stop":826.322,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and stricken for (Inaudible) presumably by the prosecution.","start":826.322,"stop":831.089,"duration":4.77}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Absolutely, sir.","start":831.089,"stop":832.018,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":832.018,"stop":832.892,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, getting back to the -- to the question which Mr. Justice asked me.","start":832.892,"stop":838.996,"duration":6.1},{"text":"Judge Carter testified that he had known one Negro to serve on a grand jury in 21 years, only one.","start":838.996,"stop":847.349,"duration":8.35},{"text":"Now, he had -- he had drawn most of these grand juries and addressed most of them.","start":847.349,"stop":852.261,"duration":4.91},{"text":"Our contention made by way of motion was that Negroes did not served through some design, either because they were lift off of the jury rules all together or somewhere between the time of placing them on the roles and getting them to serve by reason of some design of the State of Alabama, they never got on a grand jury.","start":852.261,"stop":874.116,"duration":21.86}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, what's the method by which the 18 are selected?","start":874.116,"stop":877.469,"duration":3.35},{"text":"Does the judge just select them?","start":877.469,"stop":879.513,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh sure.","start":879.513,"stop":879.899,"duration":0.39},{"text":"They are put in a hat -- handkerchief put over the hat, placed over the hat.","start":879.899,"stop":882.886,"duration":2.99},{"text":"I believe that's correct from the Solicitor of Montgomery County here and he draws them out.","start":882.886,"stop":888.816,"duration":5.93},{"text":"There is no contention on the part of petitioner that the judge has a method of knowing which are Negroes or which are white.","start":888.816,"stop":896.753,"duration":7.94}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But it so happened I gather --","start":896.753,"stop":897.009,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"But he does draw them out of the hat from under the handkerchief.","start":897.009,"stop":899.89,"duration":2.88}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And your position is that over 21 years.","start":899.89,"stop":902.382,"duration":2.49}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":902.382,"stop":903.407,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Although there had been this process followed and in the hat would be a number of names of Negroes.","start":903.407,"stop":909.946,"duration":6.54}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":909.946,"stop":910.54,"duration":0.59},{"text":"Well, no, sir, we do not admit that.","start":910.54,"stop":912.678,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You do not admit that, I see.","start":912.678,"stop":914.485,"duration":1.81},{"text":"In any event, only one Negro over the 21 years ever had his name drawn from the hat, is that it?","start":914.485,"stop":920.225,"duration":5.74}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"According to the testimony of Judge Carter.","start":920.225,"stop":922.823,"duration":2.6},{"text":"Now, Judge Carter remembered positively one Negro serving, but he could not remember as many as two or four serving according to his testimony.","start":922.823,"stop":934.532,"duration":11.71}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Hall.","start":934.532,"stop":935.373,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir, Mr. Justice Frankfurter.","start":935.373,"stop":936.227,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Do I understand a right that the second trial, the trial in which there was (Inaudible) in which they had this conviction which you refer, was on the original indictment.","start":936.227,"stop":950.794,"duration":14.57}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":950.794,"stop":952.597,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Please refresh my recollection because I ought to remember this but I don't.","start":952.597,"stop":956.998,"duration":4.4},{"text":"When the case was here, 1954 --","start":956.998,"stop":960.926,"duration":3.93}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":960.926,"stop":961.908,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- was the question of the makeup of the grand jury panel as well as the selection urged on this before?","start":961.908,"stop":970.74,"duration":8.83}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir, Mr. Justice Frankfurter.","start":970.74,"stop":972.779,"duration":2.04},{"text":"It was argued extensively.","start":972.779,"stop":974.912,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't mean to draw any instance.","start":974.912,"stop":976.05,"duration":1.14},{"text":"I just want to know the fact.","start":976.05,"stop":977.175,"duration":1.13},{"text":"That was true, wasn't it?","start":977.175,"stop":978.19,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":978.19,"stop":979.194,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It was urged and argued -- the briefs --","start":979.194,"stop":983.054,"duration":3.86}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":983.054,"stop":983.196,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- argument and accounted by counsel for the State.","start":983.196,"stop":985.578,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir, of course.","start":985.578,"stop":987.605,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And you are now -- you are now -- you are now again challenging the validity, the constitutional of validity of the indictment because of the composition of the panel, is that right?","start":987.605,"stop":1005.693,"duration":18.09}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1005.693,"stop":1006.791,"duration":1.1},{"text":"That is one reason, Mr. Justice Frankfurter and the other reason we attack the indictment was because our contention is that there was no sufficient legal evidence before such grand jury as is required by a statute of the State of Alabama on which they could base the indictment.","start":1006.791,"stop":1026.837,"duration":20.05}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you challenge the -- the Constitution of the petty jury also?","start":1026.837,"stop":1032.454,"duration":5.62}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"We did challenge that, sir.","start":1032.454,"stop":1033.905,"duration":1.45},{"text":"We had a hearing on this, Mr. Chief Justice Warren.","start":1033.905,"stop":1035.95,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But what is the fact in regard to petty juries in that county in recent years?","start":1035.95,"stop":1043.247,"duration":7.3}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"We set out in our motion for pushing the petty jury, call to hear this case the fact that the Negro population of Montgomery County, Alabama constitutes something like 40% from the total population of the County.","start":1043.247,"stop":1061.593,"duration":18.35},{"text":"They contended in that motion that from nothing to no more than 10% that no jury -- put it this way, sir.","start":1061.593,"stop":1072.747,"duration":11.15},{"text":"No jury ever was composed of more than 10% no panel or the jury role itself did not contain the names of more than 10% of its total makeup over Negroes.","start":1072.747,"stop":1089.964,"duration":17.22}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Does that mean that if the -- if the hundred every time, you never had a panel that had more than 10 Negroes --","start":1089.964,"stop":1094.896,"duration":4.93}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Never had that more than 10 --","start":1094.896,"stop":1095.4,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- names, is that it?","start":1095.4,"stop":1097.733,"duration":2.33}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, in --","start":1097.733,"stop":1098.796,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) any concern on petty juries?","start":1098.796,"stop":1102.963,"duration":4.17}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- yes, sir, Mr. Chief Justice Warren.","start":1102.963,"stop":1105.875,"duration":2.91},{"text":"We must admit that Negroes have served on petty juries.","start":1105.875,"stop":1109.286,"duration":3.41},{"text":"I have seen them serve in Montgomery County in recent years.","start":1109.286,"stop":1112.799,"duration":3.51},{"text":"However, one of our main contentions is that Jeremiah Reeves was arrested and indicted in 1952 and as Judge Eugene Carter says, “Until recent years, they have had very few Negroes on the jury.","start":1112.799,"stop":1127.613,"duration":14.81},{"text":"And in 1952, I don't believe they had any.”","start":1127.613,"stop":1131.488,"duration":3.88},{"text":"In 1955, I have to reflect that Negroes are serving on petty juries in Montgomery County, Alabama.","start":1131.488,"stop":1138.663,"duration":7.17},{"text":"Now --","start":1138.663,"stop":1138.932,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"By way of information.","start":1138.932,"stop":1140.446,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1140.446,"stop":1143.415,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is the situation also from your point of view is ameliorated or changed as to grand jury -- serve on grand jury on the panel from which grand jury to draw?","start":1143.415,"stop":1156.733,"duration":13.32}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Frankfurter, I do not know.","start":1156.733,"stop":1160.221,"duration":3.49},{"text":"I do not know of any Negro who has served on a grand jury in Montgomery County at any time.","start":1160.221,"stop":1167.778,"duration":7.56},{"text":"On this hearing, we questioned several Negroes and leaders there in the city of Montgomery, well educated persons, persons with position and none of them knew of any Negroes who had served on a grand jury.","start":1167.778,"stop":1182.628,"duration":14.85}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you practice in Montgomery, Mr. Hall?","start":1182.628,"stop":1184.856,"duration":2.23}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"I am in Birmingham, Mr. Justice.","start":1184.856,"stop":1186.197,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In Birmingham.","start":1186.197,"stop":1187.12,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"But I have also practiced in Montgomery and all of the State of Alabama.","start":1187.12,"stop":1193.104,"duration":5.98},{"text":"I have seen, however, in the City of Montgomery, Alabama as many as three or four Negroes on petty jury in recent years.","start":1193.104,"stop":1203.081,"duration":9.98}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Criminal petty jury?","start":1203.081,"stop":1204.884,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"I couldn't be sure, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, possibly so, but that has been in recent years.","start":1204.884,"stop":1211.474,"duration":6.59},{"text":"I must stress that.","start":1211.474,"stop":1213.117,"duration":1.64},{"text":"There has been a change and our contention is that the grand jury which indicted Jeremiah Reeves in 1952 was made up under that whole system which of course has changed recently and that at that time, it was greatly wrong and deprived the rights guaranteed him by United States constitution and that, the system by which they selected persons to serve was designed to discriminate against Negroes because of their race.","start":1213.117,"stop":1246.426,"duration":33.31}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1246.426,"stop":1259.437,"duration":13.01}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir, Mr. Justice Whittaker.","start":1259.437,"stop":1262.156,"duration":2.72},{"text":"The Alabama law requires that the composition of a grand jury can be attacked only by a plea in abatement and that such plea must be made in any case before arraignment.","start":1262.156,"stop":1275.15,"duration":12.99}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1275.15,"stop":1277.289,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"In 1952, sir, as we try to outline to begin with, Jeremiah Reeves is arrested on November 10th, 1952.","start":1277.289,"stop":1285.826,"duration":8.54},{"text":"He was kept in the Montgomery City Jail for --","start":1285.826,"stop":1289.066,"duration":3.24}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1289.066,"stop":1291.271,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1291.271,"stop":1292.66,"duration":1.39},{"text":"He was kept in the Montgomery City Jail four or five hours where he was questioned intensively.","start":1292.66,"stop":1297.732,"duration":5.07},{"text":"This record, the previous record will show that.","start":1297.732,"stop":1301.463,"duration":3.73},{"text":"He was then taken from the city jail to Kilby Prison, a penitentiary where the record said and where the testimony was to be effective that he was placed in the electric chair and some other things and kept there from November 10th to November 14th.","start":1301.463,"stop":1321.952,"duration":20.49},{"text":"But this was -- we're not urging this, Mr. Justice Whittaker but in order to make the point that he did meet the requirement.","start":1321.952,"stop":1330.543,"duration":8.59},{"text":"He was taken to Montgomery City Jail to Kilby Prison where he was kept from November 10th to November 14th.","start":1330.543,"stop":1336.733,"duration":6.19}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the -- the idea was that the confession which --","start":1336.733,"stop":1339.486,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1339.486,"stop":1340.524,"duration":1.04},{"text":"Whether in this confession --","start":1340.524,"stop":1341.239,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- has been thrown out by the previous decision was gained by bringing him in alongside the electric chair and telling him (Voice Overlap) --","start":1341.239,"stop":1346.43,"duration":5.19}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"That was the confession on the previous trial.","start":1346.43,"stop":1349.37,"duration":2.94},{"text":"At least he was queried intensively.","start":1349.37,"stop":1352.067,"duration":2.7},{"text":"He was kept incommunicado.","start":1352.067,"stop":1354.945,"duration":2.88},{"text":"We urged on the previous hearing that he was threatened.","start":1354.945,"stop":1357.92,"duration":2.98},{"text":"From the 10th to the 14th, he was not allowed to see his parents to have counsel or to see anyone.","start":1357.92,"stop":1363.548,"duration":5.63},{"text":"On the 14th, allegedly, he had made certain statements and has made certain confessions.","start":1363.548,"stop":1369.444,"duration":5.9},{"text":"Now, on that same day, he was allowed to see his mother for the first time.But on that same day, he was indicted by the Montgomery County grand jury.","start":1369.444,"stop":1379.252,"duration":9.81},{"text":"Now, he -- on the next day, the 15th, he was arraigned.","start":1379.252,"stop":1384,"duration":4.75}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"He had counsel --","start":1384,"stop":1385.134,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"He had counsel on that day.","start":1385.134,"stop":1386.742,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, where did he get counsel?","start":1386.742,"stop":1388.149,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"He -- and that, we do not know, sir.","start":1388.149,"stop":1390.653,"duration":2.5},{"text":"We were not the counsel for him at that time, but this -- the man that he had as his lawyer at that time and tried to see him at Kilby Prison and according to the record on the first trial -- on the first trial had been refused, admitted.","start":1390.653,"stop":1403.83,"duration":13.18},{"text":"So, he had no chance to confer with.We would like to also point out the fact that on the 15th, when he was arraigned, he had not been served of the copy of his indictment nor did he know who the members of the grand jury that had indicted him were.","start":1403.83,"stop":1425.126,"duration":21.3}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Hall, what was the ground in which the state court denied your motion to --","start":1425.126,"stop":1430.423,"duration":5.3}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Motion to quash?","start":1430.423,"stop":1430.833,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, motion to quash --","start":1430.833,"stop":1431.974,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"It came too late --","start":1431.974,"stop":1433.413,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It came too late.","start":1433.413,"stop":1434.905,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Counsel, may I attempt to make this point a little clearer?","start":1434.905,"stop":1440.518,"duration":5.61},{"text":"Counsel for petitioner on the first hearing, on the day of arraignment, requested a continuance from the trial court for the purpose of drawing up motions going towards an attack on the indictment.","start":1440.518,"stop":1455.999,"duration":15.48},{"text":"The trial court refused that continuance.","start":1455.999,"stop":1458.307,"duration":2.31},{"text":"He was required to plead.","start":1458.307,"stop":1460.354,"duration":2.05},{"text":"At that time, they made a plea of not guilty, not guilty by reason of insanity.","start":1460.354,"stop":1465.621,"duration":5.27},{"text":"Now, that was in 1952.","start":1465.621,"stop":1469.07,"duration":3.45},{"text":"Subsequent to that, he again attempted to attack the indictment and the trial court held that the attack came too late in as much as he had already made a plea to the merits.","start":1469.07,"stop":1484.256,"duration":15.19},{"text":"On this hearing --","start":1484.256,"stop":1486.857,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Let's see.","start":1486.857,"stop":1487.275,"duration":0.42},{"text":"He made the plea, you tell us because he was denied a continuance --","start":1487.275,"stop":1491.193,"duration":3.92}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1491.193,"stop":1491.277,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- which he sought for the expressed purpose of making an attack in the indictment, isn't it?","start":1491.277,"stop":1495.064,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1495.064,"stop":1496.665,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, that was --","start":1496.665,"stop":1497.175,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Reeves had been indicted on the 14th.","start":1497.175,"stop":1499.796,"duration":2.62},{"text":"He was arraigned on the 15th and at the time of arraignment, he was required to plea.","start":1499.796,"stop":1504.176,"duration":4.38},{"text":"He asked for continuance, the judge says no so he had plea.","start":1504.176,"stop":1508.282,"duration":4.11}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"He was tried on the 26th?","start":1508.282,"stop":1510.065,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1510.065,"stop":1510.792,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Under what, on the same month?","start":1510.792,"stop":1512.242,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"On the same month.","start":1512.242,"stop":1513.5,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, he had a lawyer and as I understand the point -- well, can you tell us precisely when he had a lawyer?","start":1513.5,"stop":1520.856,"duration":7.36},{"text":"Was it on the 14th the day he was indicted?","start":1520.856,"stop":1524.592,"duration":3.74}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"He was not allowed to see anyone until the 14th and afterwards, so it had to be the 14th, sir.","start":1524.592,"stop":1530.956,"duration":6.36}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"It's important to me because I want to know how much time intervened from the time he had a lawyer until he had to plea in this case.","start":1530.956,"stop":1541.552,"duration":10.6}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Please excuse me, Mr. Justice Whittaker.","start":1541.552,"stop":1543.562,"duration":2.01},{"text":"I have here somewhere in the brief.","start":1543.562,"stop":1550.058,"duration":6.5},{"text":"On page 7 --","start":1550.058,"stop":1551.75,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Page 7?","start":1551.75,"stop":1551.786,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of -- of petitioners brief under (1), at the bottom of the page.","start":1551.786,"stop":1559.389,"duration":7.6},{"text":"We set out some of this.","start":1559.389,"stop":1560.833,"duration":1.44},{"text":"At the bottom of the page, we set out at the last paragraph.","start":1560.833,"stop":1568.805,"duration":7.97},{"text":"He was taken from the county jail, situated in the City of Montgomery, Alabama where he was kept five or six minutes and then taken immediately to Kilby Prison, the State penitentiary, situated in the same County where he was put in the test cell, questioned and threatened without advise of counsel and not allowed to see his parents from Monday, November 10th until the afternoon of Thursday, November 14th after he had made certain admissions and culprit statements when his mother was allowed to see him.","start":1568.805,"stop":1595.338,"duration":26.53},{"text":"I don't know if counsel was allowed to see him that afternoon or the morning of the 15th, but I know he saw no one until the afternoon of November 14th and he was required to plea on trial for his life on the morning of November 15th.","start":1595.338,"stop":1609.741,"duration":14.4}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And he was actually indicted on the 14th, the same say he first saw his mother.","start":1609.741,"stop":1611.907,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir the same day.","start":1611.907,"stop":1614.344,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So at most, it had to be within 24-hours.","start":1614.344,"stop":1617.421,"duration":3.08}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1617.421,"stop":1618.737,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, now did I understand you to say earlier that -- does the record show that his mother had retained a lawyer who had tried to see him between the 10th and 14th --","start":1618.737,"stop":1627.342,"duration":8.61}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"The record of previous hearing, in the record of the previous hearing shows that some attorney, Mr. (Inaudible) I believe attempted to see him at Kilby Prison.","start":1627.342,"stop":1638.996,"duration":11.65}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's between the 10th and the 14th.","start":1638.996,"stop":1640.44,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Between the 10th and the 14th and was to -- there is some contention.","start":1640.44,"stop":1645.608,"duration":5.17},{"text":"We don't have it in this record.","start":1645.608,"stop":1647.062,"duration":1.45},{"text":"We didn't go into that issue.","start":1647.062,"stop":1650.521,"duration":3.46},{"text":"On --","start":1650.521,"stop":1651.146,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there anything in the record that shows that he actually, at the time that he made his motion to continue (Inaudible).","start":1651.146,"stop":1659.798,"duration":8.65}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"For the motion for continuance, Mr. Justice Clark?","start":1659.798,"stop":1661.926,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"Contend that he was going to raise the question of attack on the grand jury.","start":1661.926,"stop":1670.702,"duration":8.78}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't --","start":1670.702,"stop":1671.311,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) a motion for continuance is made and to say what grounds or what is the further motion.","start":1671.311,"stop":1680.2,"duration":8.89}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"I am not sure of that contention, Mr. Justice Clark, but somewhere in the record, there is a suggestion.","start":1680.2,"stop":1690.567,"duration":10.37},{"text":"I don't know if it's in this record, previous record because we argued the same point on the cause that came up before.","start":1690.567,"stop":1697.943,"duration":7.38},{"text":"I believe in that record and on that brief, we set out the counsel and -- and indicated the place in the record where it was that counsel wanted to make a motion or I didn't make a motion for continuance for the purpose that argued on his motion for continuance that he wanted to attack the indictment and go into that, but they refused to grant him continuance or he wanted to study the matter.","start":1697.943,"stop":1720.967,"duration":23.02},{"text":"I'm -- I'm not sure, Mr. Justice Clark.","start":1720.967,"stop":1721.732,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"He made a motion to quash.","start":1721.732,"stop":1725.104,"duration":3.37},{"text":"He made -- he has to make a motion to quash.","start":1725.104,"stop":1727.632,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1727.632,"stop":1728.049,"duration":0.42},{"text":"He made a motion to quash subsequent to his plea on the arraignment.","start":1728.049,"stop":1732.277,"duration":4.23}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, did he -- on the 15th, the record showed that he came in and made a motion to continue the arraignment and then go over it.","start":1732.277,"stop":1745.208,"duration":12.93},{"text":"The judge said he denied it.","start":1745.208,"stop":1746.777,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1746.777,"stop":1746.949,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"Can you say what the grounds were?Now, my question was and I understand (Inaudible) it's in the record that was here before.","start":1746.949,"stop":1755.79,"duration":8.84}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1755.79,"stop":1756.748,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"That record should show that at that time, the counsel stated that he wish to attack the merits.","start":1756.748,"stop":1766.157,"duration":9.41}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Clark, he also suggested that he subsequently on the trial made a motion to quash, I believe.","start":1766.157,"stop":1774.233,"duration":8.08}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"That was the 13th.","start":1774.233,"stop":1775.591,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"On the 13th, yes sir, but that was after --","start":1775.591,"stop":1778.339,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"The arraignment.","start":1778.339,"stop":1778.74,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the arraignment and everything else, but he actually made a motion to quash the indictment.","start":1778.74,"stop":1782.494,"duration":3.75},{"text":"And the trial court held then that he came too late.","start":1782.494,"stop":1784.849,"duration":2.36},{"text":"He had already pleaded.","start":1784.849,"stop":1791.275,"duration":6.43},{"text":"On the previous hearing, in this honorable Court, it is our understanding that the reversal was predicated on the Commission and the evidence of an illegal confession or certain statements made by petitioner alleged to it and made by the petitioner.","start":1791.275,"stop":1816.521,"duration":25.25},{"text":"The record of the previous file indicates that no written confession was introduced into evidence or read to the jury, but that certain words or certain statements alleged to have been made to the prosecuting witness, Mrs. (Inaudible), and to a state official were repeated for the benefit of the jury or went to the jury.","start":1816.521,"stop":1850.865,"duration":34.34},{"text":"On the second trial, no confession was read to the jury nor did Mrs. (Inaudible) this time repeat verbatim what had been said to her previously, but she admitted on the stand that at the time she allegedly identified petitioner on November 12, the state is important.","start":1850.865,"stop":1882.718,"duration":31.85},{"text":"Before she viewed him through a one-way window as he stood alone in a cell, it's either the city or county jail that she had been given a statement by a police official which indicated that the man which she was looking at had confessed to the crime.","start":1882.718,"stop":1906.942,"duration":24.22}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"This record shows that?","start":1906.942,"stop":1908.104,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1908.104,"stop":1909.819,"duration":1.71},{"text":"They referred to (Inaudible).","start":1909.819,"stop":1914.007,"duration":4.19},{"text":"Now, the State is under the assumption that they did not introduce a confession.","start":1914.007,"stop":1922.096,"duration":8.09},{"text":"Our contention is that if it was ever introduced, it was introduced this time too, because a prosecuting witness indicates from everything she says and from her actions and the fact that she had to talk with the man.","start":1922.096,"stop":1937.329,"duration":15.23},{"text":"She looked at him through a one way window.She did not have to go into the cell.","start":1937.329,"stop":1941.295,"duration":3.97},{"text":"She had to go in and talk to him.","start":1941.295,"stop":1942.857,"duration":1.56},{"text":"She saw the statement before she went in and then she still had to go in and talk to him and have a conversation with him before she could come out and say she's identified.","start":1942.857,"stop":1953.385,"duration":10.53},{"text":"But her entire identification was based upon that culprit statement or whatever that confession was.","start":1953.385,"stop":1961.428,"duration":8.04},{"text":"The State certainly don't have to introduce it into evidence, only by introducing her and letting her point the finger on the petitioner and identifying him.","start":1961.428,"stop":1973.815,"duration":12.39},{"text":"The State's whole case is grounded upon the identification of the prosecuting witness and the corroborating testimony of one witness called -- his name is Clark who allegedly picked up a colored boy somewhere in the vicinity of the neighborhood where this crime took place on the day in question.","start":1973.815,"stop":1997.579,"duration":23.76},{"text":"And this man, this witness that remember everything in the world about petitioner, but he couldn't even remember the day he talked to him in prison.","start":1997.579,"stop":2009.331,"duration":11.75},{"text":"And he -- and the record of the previous hearing, again, this hearing will show that he could identify him until he talk to him, so whatever admissions were made for the basis of his identification.","start":2009.331,"stop":2026.613,"duration":17.28},{"text":"Assuming that we had been allowed on a proper hearing to question those people, those persons who must have appeared before the grand jury and as much as the State's whole case rested up on that identification, if we could have shown that the indictment was granted upon these illegal admissions, then it seems to me on the decisions of this Court and under the Federal Constitution decision and under the law of Alabama which is clearly set out in our statute and in here looking at the State where the Supreme Court is held that were -- the legality of evidence before the grand jury when it's brought up on a motion to quash must be decided by the trial court before they can go on to hear the case on the merits.","start":2026.613,"stop":2079.152,"duration":52.54}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2079.152,"stop":2084.65,"duration":5.5}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":2084.65,"stop":2086.014,"duration":1.36},{"text":"The State brought up Costello and while we didn't discuss it, we didn't take issue there.","start":2086.014,"stop":2097.018,"duration":11},{"text":"It seems to us that Costello appears sort of different situation and as much as it's a criminal case to those in the Federal Courts and Costello is relying upon the Fifth Amendment and whatever rights he might have under the Fifth Amendment.","start":2097.018,"stop":2114.357,"duration":17.34},{"text":"It was his contention that if the Fifth Amendment guaranteed him nothing that this Court should setout certain rules by which grand jury should go before and bringing in an indictment.","start":2114.357,"stop":2129.464,"duration":15.11},{"text":"The Court, Mr. Justice Black's opinion held that the Fifth Amendment guaranteed him nothing only that -- all the murders and infamous trials should begin by indictments are presented.","start":2129.464,"stop":2148.625,"duration":19.16},{"text":"And in a review of the grand jury system, he pointed out that they've been more or less left on their own.","start":2148.625,"stop":2157.051,"duration":8.43},{"text":"However, we are relying upon an Alabama statute which says that only legal evidence can go to grand jury.","start":2157.051,"stop":2167.075,"duration":10.02}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2167.075,"stop":2173.017,"duration":5.94}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"They didn't say the statute was set aside, sir.","start":2173.017,"stop":2177.281,"duration":4.26},{"text":"They absolutely refused to give us a hearing on our motion.","start":2177.281,"stop":2181.87,"duration":4.59}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"On the ground that you're out of time, was it?","start":2181.87,"stop":2184.775,"duration":2.91}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"On the grounds that we -- that there was no merit (Inaudible), sir.","start":2184.775,"stop":2188.859,"duration":4.08},{"text":"They absolutely refused to give us a hearing on our motion.","start":2188.859,"stop":2192.492,"duration":3.63},{"text":"I don't know what the -- I don't recall exactly what the Court held.","start":2192.492,"stop":2197.481,"duration":4.99},{"text":"But in addition to that -- that statute incidentally while I check this, we had an Alabama case to back our position up and that was the Hill case which we just mentioned and which we cite in the brief, Hill against State 20 Alabama (Inaudible) which was a -- a conviction for a liquor law violation where the defendant alleged the grand jury which returned the indictment.","start":2197.481,"stop":2226.132,"duration":28.65},{"text":"It has no legal evidence before it and that the indictment should be quashed.","start":2226.132,"stop":2230.577,"duration":4.45},{"text":"The trial court overruled it and went up to the State Supreme Court and the State Supreme Court held that there was a merit in his contention and that the -- that the motion presented an issue of fact to be determined by the trial court before the defendant could be required to plea on the merits.","start":2230.577,"stop":2246.276,"duration":15.7},{"text":"But in this particular case that the Supreme Court of Alabama would not --","start":2246.276,"stop":2252.286,"duration":6.01}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Where does it appear why -- are the reasons stated why the motion to quash was denied?","start":2252.286,"stop":2258.503,"duration":6.22}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":2258.503,"stop":2259.761,"duration":1.26},{"text":"The trial court gave no reason.","start":2259.761,"stop":2261.43,"duration":1.67},{"text":"They just overruled on this.","start":2261.43,"stop":2263.225,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is the order?","start":2263.225,"stop":2265.075,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"Find it for me.","start":2265.075,"stop":2266.97,"duration":1.89},{"text":"Would you allow him to find (Inaudible)?","start":2266.97,"stop":2305.816,"duration":38.85},{"text":"Record 18 and Record 207.","start":2305.816,"stop":2315.843,"duration":10.03}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is this at page 19, additional judgment and pleadings?","start":2315.843,"stop":2320.614,"duration":4.77}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"18.","start":2320.614,"stop":2321.554,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"18?","start":2321.554,"stop":2322.501,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"On the record, sir.","start":2322.501,"stop":2325.799,"duration":3.3}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Does the record of the proceedings which led up to those judgments anywhere?","start":2325.799,"stop":2329.467,"duration":3.67}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"On page 207 of the record, motion to quash indictment (Inaudible) on page 207 of the proceeding, sir.","start":2329.467,"stop":2352.006,"duration":22.54}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, apparently, the State objected to the motion on single ground, wasn't it, that it came too late?","start":2352.006,"stop":2360.763,"duration":8.76}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"The State objected, Your honor.","start":2360.763,"stop":2362.179,"duration":1.42},{"text":"I -- I recall the trial court giving no reason they overruling the motion and we took exception.","start":2362.179,"stop":2367.795,"duration":5.62}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You're right that he says nothing, but I notice that the Solicitor for the State, the top of page 207 states his reasons for objecting that it comes too late.","start":2367.795,"stop":2377.953,"duration":10.16},{"text":"Now, the trial judge says -- he says “Considered opinion that the motion should be denied”.","start":2377.953,"stop":2382.771,"duration":4.82}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2382.771,"stop":2383.325,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that right?","start":2383.325,"stop":2383.922,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Peter A. Hall","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2383.922,"stop":2396.22,"duration":12.3},{"text":"If Your Honors please, I'm don't want to take all of the time.","start":2396.22,"stop":2403.385,"duration":7.17},{"text":"We have this divided time but we have another argument which we wanted to present, another point.","start":2403.385,"stop":2410.825,"duration":7.44},{"text":"The petitioner understands that an ordinary circumstances, it's unnecessary to re-indict, to re-arraign a man simply because -- because it's been reversed on appeal.","start":2410.825,"stop":2420.53,"duration":9.71},{"text":"Usually, the error, if it appears, is some error which goes on the trial of the cause, an error in ruling on the part of the Court, errors of otherwise.","start":2420.53,"stop":2431.611,"duration":11.08},{"text":"But in this particular cause, we think it is particularly urgent and under the circumstances here, the trial court's refusal to allow petitioner to withdraw his pleas previously in it, which petitioner asked first before attacking the Court's position and asking for reindictment and rearraignment.","start":2431.611,"stop":2452.757,"duration":21.15},{"text":"Petitioner asked that he be allowed to withdraw his pleas in it at his previous arraignment in order that he might attack the legality of his indictment.","start":2452.757,"stop":2463.39,"duration":10.63},{"text":"The trial court absolutely refused to allow him to withdraw his pleas.","start":2463.39,"stop":2468.355,"duration":4.97},{"text":"Now, it is admitted by petitioner that the trial court had discretion to refuse or to grant that request to withdraw pleas.","start":2468.355,"stop":2478.991,"duration":10.64},{"text":"But we submit that under the circumstances, his refusal to allow to withdraw was arbitrary to the extent that it was -- it's a revisable error and that it did deny the defendant, a very substantial right guaranteed him by these laws of Alabama and by the federal laws.","start":2478.991,"stop":2501.407,"duration":22.42},{"text":"Thank you very much.","start":2501.407,"stop":2507.212,"duration":5.8}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Thetford.","start":2507.212,"stop":2508.783,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":2508.783,"stop":2514.673,"duration":5.89},{"text":"We, my colleague and I, Mr. Stewart are here as the Solicitor and Deputy Solicitor who prosecuted this case, prosecuted it both the first time and the second time.","start":2514.673,"stop":2528.778,"duration":14.11},{"text":"We're here by order and direction of Attorney General of the State of Alabama.","start":2528.778,"stop":2533.846,"duration":5.07},{"text":"We are dividing our time and I propose to argue in this order, is the Board of Jury Supervisors of Montgomery County systematically excluding Negroes because of race or color and let me explain this that what I say would apply equally to grand or petty juries because they're all drawn out of the same box.","start":2533.846,"stop":2558.631,"duration":24.78},{"text":"Does due process require the reindictment, rearraignment of the defendant for a second trial?","start":2558.631,"stop":2565.832,"duration":7.2},{"text":"Did due process require the trial court to allow the defendant to withdraw his pleas of not guilty and not guilty by reason of insanity entered on November the 15th, 1952 upon a subsequent trial held after reversal of this case by the Supreme Court of the new -- the request being made on May 30th, 1955 and should the defendant have been allowed to inquire into this efficiency of the evidence before the grand jury which indicted him.","start":2565.832,"stop":2598.071,"duration":32.24},{"text":"Those are the four of the points which have been argued.","start":2598.071,"stop":2600.693,"duration":2.62},{"text":"Mr. Stewart will cover the two remaining points which are the certain remarks which were made and certainly a request that was made in the qualifying of the jury or trial, the actual trial jury and the question of excluding the public from a court room during the trial of case -- a rape case, case of this nature.","start":2600.693,"stop":2624.221,"duration":23.53}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you mention the question of the confessions of --","start":2624.221,"stop":2628.544,"duration":4.32}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"There is no question of a confession in here.","start":2628.544,"stop":2631.409,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"What -- are we going to deal with it?","start":2631.409,"stop":2635.425,"duration":4.02}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"What's the point that you talk about it?","start":2635.425,"stop":2637.726,"duration":2.3}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there is.","start":2637.726,"stop":2638.281,"duration":0.55},{"text":"The State offered no confession or anything approaching a confession.","start":2638.281,"stop":2641.647,"duration":3.37},{"text":"He said so, but I'm -- and I'm going to answer that.","start":2641.647,"stop":2644.622,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":2644.622,"stop":2645.073,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"But that is simply our concern on the statement of the fact.","start":2645.073,"stop":2647.542,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Very well but you're going to deal with it.","start":2647.542,"stop":2648.725,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"I will.","start":2648.725,"stop":2649.378,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll -- we'll recess now, Mr. Thetford.","start":2649.378,"stop":2653.787,"duration":4.41}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - January 09, 1958","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13523","transcript":[{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"-- getting into my argument as -- on the systematic exclusion of Negroes from the jury.","start":0,"stop":7.126,"duration":7.13},{"text":"I would like to answer Mr. Justice Frankfurter's question as to the confession.","start":7.126,"stop":12.416,"duration":5.29},{"text":"The State of Alabama introduced no confession in the case that we are now considering.","start":12.416,"stop":19.316,"duration":6.9},{"text":"It might be helpful to the Court if I went a little into the background.","start":19.316,"stop":24.367,"duration":5.05},{"text":"I think it will probably answer several questions.","start":24.367,"stop":28.417,"duration":4.05},{"text":"Jeremiah Reeves was arrested on November 12, 1952.He was carried for safekeeping, took care of the penitentiary which is a short distance form the City of Montgomery.","start":28.417,"stop":44.414,"duration":16},{"text":"He made a confession on -- the 12th was on Monday.","start":44.414,"stop":52.093,"duration":7.68},{"text":"He made a confession on Tuesday, Tuesday afternoon.","start":52.093,"stop":57.578,"duration":5.49},{"text":"He made the confession in my presence.","start":57.578,"stop":60.085,"duration":2.51},{"text":"That confession was recorded and I believe later reduced to writing and signed.","start":60.085,"stop":69.827,"duration":9.74},{"text":"On Wednesday morning, he was carried to the City Hall, the police headquarters of Montgomery as located in the City Hall.","start":69.827,"stop":79.524,"duration":9.7},{"text":"And there, he was identified by (Inaudible), who at that time was a 19-year-old white woman who identified him as the person who had raped her on July the 28th.","start":79.524,"stop":94.081,"duration":14.56},{"text":"He was subsequently -- now, according to -- we've got in kind of into both records in this case and I presume you'll let me maybe refer to the first record.","start":94.081,"stop":101.732,"duration":7.65}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":101.732,"stop":103.213,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a -- here in Court.","start":103.213,"stop":105.872,"duration":2.66},{"text":"On the trial -- on his firs trial, both he and his mother testified that she had seen him on Wednesday which would be November the 12th.In the second trial that --","start":105.872,"stop":120.469,"duration":14.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":120.469,"stop":124.45,"duration":3.98}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the -- no, he was arrested on the 10th, Monday the 10th.","start":124.45,"stop":132.994,"duration":8.54},{"text":"On the 12th, he said that he -- that is in the first record.","start":132.994,"stop":137.509,"duration":4.51},{"text":"Both he and his mother testified that they saw each other on the -- on the 12th.","start":137.509,"stop":142.519,"duration":5.01},{"text":"Now, in the second trial which -- to where the trials go.","start":142.519,"stop":145.861,"duration":3.34},{"text":"They both testified that it was the 13th, rather than the 12th.","start":145.861,"stop":151.653,"duration":5.79},{"text":"He was arraigned on the -- I mean indicted on the 14th and arraigned on the 15th.","start":151.653,"stop":156.982,"duration":5.33},{"text":"Now, in the first trial, we had -- well now, we don't admit all that he says in his -- in his pleading as the way that confession was taken.","start":156.982,"stop":169.597,"duration":12.62},{"text":"We have never admitted that, but we had serious doubts as to whether it was taken in a manner that was legal.","start":169.597,"stop":177.084,"duration":7.49},{"text":"We did not introduce the written confession or the recorded confession in the first trial.","start":177.084,"stop":184.397,"duration":7.31},{"text":"We did introduce in the first trial certain remarks that he made to Mrs. Crowder at the police headquarters on the 12th.","start":184.397,"stop":195.123,"duration":10.73},{"text":"We also introduced testimony from his psychiatrist who had examined him some time later.","start":195.123,"stop":201.145,"duration":6.02},{"text":"And in the testimony of the psychiatrist, there was a confession involved.","start":201.145,"stop":208.412,"duration":7.27},{"text":"That was the basis on which this Court reversed in the first case.","start":208.412,"stop":216.715,"duration":8.3},{"text":"In the second case --","start":216.715,"stop":217.328,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"When -- may I interrupt?","start":217.328,"stop":218.397,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":218.397,"stop":219.287,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Refreshment or recollection.","start":219.287,"stop":220.587,"duration":1.3},{"text":"When were the so-called confessions which were introduced with -- on the record that came here?","start":220.587,"stop":227.98,"duration":7.39},{"text":"When was it made?","start":227.98,"stop":229.911,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"One was a conversation that he had with the complaining witness --","start":229.911,"stop":232.956,"duration":3.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":232.956,"stop":233.422,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"-- on Wednesday morning.","start":233.422,"stop":235.9,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Wednesday.","start":235.9,"stop":236.529,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"On Wednesday.","start":236.529,"stop":237.598,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The crime on Monday.","start":237.598,"stop":238.692,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Crime on Monday and on Wednesday.","start":238.692,"stop":241.059,"duration":2.37},{"text":"Now, in the second trial of this case, the --","start":241.059,"stop":244.391,"duration":3.33}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":244.391,"stop":246.796,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"He was arrested on Monday.","start":246.796,"stop":248.045,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":248.045,"stop":249.35,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Several months, sir, yes.On the second trial, we --","start":249.35,"stop":254.378,"duration":5.03}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Did he have a -- did he have a lawyer of record?","start":254.378,"stop":257.204,"duration":2.83}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, lawyer of his own choice and --","start":257.204,"stop":259.392,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean at the time -- the Monday and Wednesday, the Wednesday that the statement was made to Mrs.-- whatever her name.","start":259.392,"stop":266.996,"duration":7.6}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sure he did not.","start":266.996,"stop":268.305,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"He didn't --","start":268.305,"stop":268.463,"duration":0.16}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"I think the lawyer was employed.","start":268.463,"stop":270.174,"duration":1.71},{"text":"Maybe, I don't -- the record, it doesn't show when the lawyer was employed and I -- I can't state definitely when he was employed or -- but I am sure that he was not employed on Wednesday.","start":270.174,"stop":284.257,"duration":14.08},{"text":"Now -- however, the confession is completely out of this case.","start":284.257,"stop":288.592,"duration":4.33},{"text":"We introduced no confession and this record contains no confession of any kind, nature or description on the second trial of this case.","start":288.592,"stop":297.392,"duration":8.8}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"The claims of course is relevant to the indictment.","start":297.392,"stop":301.656,"duration":4.26}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":301.656,"stop":302.963,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":302.963,"stop":304.962,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he's -- he's claiming that.","start":304.962,"stop":306.437,"duration":1.48},{"text":"I -- I will get that.","start":306.437,"stop":307.52,"duration":1.08},{"text":"But what I wanted to clear up in the Court's mind before we got any further that there is no confession in this case.","start":307.52,"stop":312.657,"duration":5.14},{"text":"We introduced no confession of any kind.","start":312.657,"stop":315.934,"duration":3.28}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"At the trial?","start":315.934,"stop":316.604,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"At the trial.","start":316.604,"stop":317.557,"duration":0.95},{"text":"Now, what I think he possibly is referring to was introduced by the defendant, not by the State.","start":317.557,"stop":326.254,"duration":8.7},{"text":"Now, on cross-examination, you'll find this in page 237 of the record.On recross-examination of the -- of Ms. Crowder, Lawyer Hall, “Let me ask you a little something further with reference to your last identification of this defendant in November,” referring to November 1952.","start":326.254,"stop":350.488,"duration":24.23},{"text":"“Were you told on that occasion he had confessed before you looked at him?”","start":350.488,"stop":354.569,"duration":4.08},{"text":"“I was given a written statement, but it wasn't sanctioned.”","start":354.569,"stop":357.106,"duration":2.54},{"text":"Now, that is the first reference to any confession whatsoever in this case and that is in this -- I believe it's the only reference to it and it was brought out by the defendant, not by the State.","start":357.106,"stop":370.821,"duration":13.72},{"text":"“You are given a statement or a statement alleged made by this defendant”.","start":370.821,"stop":373.74,"duration":2.92},{"text":"“I suppose so.It had his name on it, but it wasn't signed.”","start":373.74,"stop":376.268,"duration":2.53},{"text":"“It did have his name on it?”","start":376.268,"stop":377.284,"duration":1.02},{"text":"“Yes.”","start":377.284,"stop":377.677,"duration":0.39},{"text":"“You were given that statement before you looked at him?”","start":377.677,"stop":382.76,"duration":5.08},{"text":"“That is right.”","start":382.76,"stop":380.605,"duration":-2.15},{"text":"“You have read that statement before you looked at him?”","start":380.605,"stop":383.935,"duration":3.33},{"text":"“Did any of the officers down there tell you he had confessed or did they make any statement at all to you with reference to that confession?”","start":383.935,"stop":390.881,"duration":6.95},{"text":"“No.”","start":390.881,"stop":395.406,"duration":4.53},{"text":"Now certainly, the State cannot be held accountable to anything that was injected into this case by the defendant.","start":395.406,"stop":402.542,"duration":7.14}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It was set for them.","start":402.542,"stop":403.47,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":403.47,"stop":404.501,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I would like to ask you a question that I would fairly understand if you would say if you prefer not to answer the question.","start":404.501,"stop":412.381,"duration":7.88},{"text":"Needless to say, I think the question is -- is not irrelevant or it's not inclusive, otherwise I wouldn't put it but it bears on -- not on this case or not on the present aspect of the case, but prior to the fact that it came here once before and we got a prosecution here.","start":412.381,"stop":430.015,"duration":17.63},{"text":"We've got a case here for a crime committed six -- merely six years ago.","start":430.015,"stop":435.618,"duration":5.6},{"text":"And I regard it as not a happy circumstance to the administration of the criminal law.","start":435.618,"stop":441.34,"duration":5.72},{"text":"I'm sure you don't either.","start":441.34,"stop":443.471,"duration":2.13},{"text":"And so I want to go back to the source of the difficulty, namely the confession.","start":443.471,"stop":448.195,"duration":4.72},{"text":"This is for my enlightenment and possibly for the future cases bearing on these confession cases that come here.","start":448.195,"stop":455.406,"duration":7.21},{"text":"Some years ago, we had a case coming here from another State.","start":455.406,"stop":460.657,"duration":5.25},{"text":"Unimportant but for all other state in which we reversed the conviction of a defendant who was probably guilty, but not tried according to what we found to be due process because of an illicit confession.","start":460.657,"stop":478.514,"duration":17.86},{"text":"And thereupon, it interested me greatly that the city from the State in which this case came here made it a practice and I assume it continues that no statement of an accused person was taken by the police, except in the presence of some disinterested witnesses.","start":478.514,"stop":499.376,"duration":20.86},{"text":"I don't mean picked by it, but -- but some people of -- of word in the community, ex officio people.","start":499.376,"stop":507.05,"duration":7.67},{"text":"First, I'd like to put to you which -- which takes care of conflict as to what the circumstances on which a confession was made and what was promised and what wasn't promised and whether the -- there was psychological, physical et cetera, et cetera.","start":507.05,"stop":521.025,"duration":13.97},{"text":"But I would like to ask an experienced prosecutor like yourself, if I may say so.","start":521.025,"stop":526.41,"duration":5.38},{"text":"What -- what -- whether you care to say, whether that would embarrass the point of view of those who have the responsibility of prosecuting the trial, whether such a practice which would take care of a lot of this business.","start":526.41,"stop":540.515,"duration":14.11},{"text":"If statements are made in the presence of this (Inaudible) as a regular thing, would you care to express their view whether that was hurtful or whether --","start":540.515,"stop":550.717,"duration":10.2}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it would not be hurtful.","start":550.717,"stop":552.194,"duration":1.48},{"text":"We have done it in our -- our more important cases, whether there was a question involved.","start":552.194,"stop":556.721,"duration":4.53},{"text":"We have called in ministers and other decent --","start":556.721,"stop":559.057,"duration":2.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Before you talk to him -- before you -- before you talked to him.","start":559.057,"stop":561.976,"duration":2.92}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"No, we have never done it.","start":561.976,"stop":563.019,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, when have you called him in?","start":563.019,"stop":565.694,"duration":2.67}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"When he's getting ready to make a confession or when -- when it's indicated that there is going to be a confession.","start":565.694,"stop":571.207,"duration":5.51}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but (Voice Overlap) --","start":571.207,"stop":571.448,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"You -- you find this, Mr. Justice --","start":571.448,"stop":572.539,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the end of a process as it was of two or three days.","start":572.539,"stop":576.081,"duration":3.54}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"You'll find this, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, and I suppose it's true in -- in all places as moderately big as Montgomery is.","start":576.081,"stop":586.015,"duration":9.93},{"text":"We handle 500 felonies a year with the staff of one prosecutor and two part-time prosecutors.","start":586.015,"stop":594.673,"duration":8.66}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Five-hundred felonies?","start":594.673,"stop":595.72,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Five-hundred felonies a year.","start":595.72,"stop":596.361,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The felony in your state means what in terms of punishment?","start":596.361,"stop":600.216,"duration":3.86}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"A year or more in the penitentiary.","start":600.216,"stop":603.805,"duration":3.59},{"text":"It's -- we would entirely have responsible people in Montgomery coming in to listen to these things if we did.","start":603.805,"stop":611.259,"duration":7.45},{"text":"I don't know whether that's going answer to your question or not, but it -- it would be very difficult to do it.","start":611.259,"stop":615.622,"duration":4.36},{"text":"It might -- it might be a very wise thing to do, I would say that.","start":615.622,"stop":624.029,"duration":8.41},{"text":"Now, I think I've answered the question as to the confession.","start":624.029,"stop":629.086,"duration":5.06},{"text":"There is no confession in this case.","start":629.086,"stop":631.103,"duration":2.02},{"text":"We're not dealing with a confession case.","start":631.103,"stop":633.117,"duration":2.01},{"text":"They don't -- they don't really reached that in their brief except in a kind of backward way where they say, “Well, the woman had seen something,” a statement, unsigned statement and thereby she -- her -- her identification of the defendant might in some way be affected.","start":633.117,"stop":652.655,"duration":19.54},{"text":"Of course, that really goes to the credibility of the witness and not to whether she can testify or not.","start":652.655,"stop":658.179,"duration":5.52},{"text":"They can ask that before a jury, but I don't think that it would preclude her from testifying if she seen a state -- unsigned statement, no -- no law that says that.","start":658.179,"stop":668.463,"duration":10.28},{"text":"I'd like now to get to the question of which I think is really the heart of this case.","start":668.463,"stop":674.48,"duration":6.02},{"text":"I -- I maybe wrong, but I think that after the question, a systematic exclusion of Negroes in the grand -- in the juries of Montgomery County really is the heart of -- of this case.","start":674.48,"stop":691.006,"duration":16.53},{"text":"The law I think is well-known to -- to us that we -- we have a board of jury supervisors composed of the two-circuit judges, the clerk of the Circuit Court, the sheriff and the probate judge who makeup the jury list in Montgomery County.","start":691.006,"stop":710.775,"duration":19.77},{"text":"It's done by local act.","start":710.775,"stop":711.846,"duration":1.07},{"text":"We're the only -- only County in the State that has that exact setup.","start":711.846,"stop":717.048,"duration":5.2},{"text":"And I think the law is -- is clearly established.","start":717.048,"stop":722.724,"duration":5.68},{"text":"They may not discriminate in any manner so far as race, all color is concerned.","start":722.724,"stop":730.852,"duration":8.13},{"text":"Also, that proportional representation as such is -- is not required by this Court.","start":730.852,"stop":736.406,"duration":5.55},{"text":"This Court simply requires that your juries, the names in the jury box be selected without discrimination.","start":736.406,"stop":746.32,"duration":9.91},{"text":"Now, the cases as I understand them also hold that findings of fact by a state court will have great weight with this Court, but of course I'm not binding on it and that this Court will look at the facts to determine whether the state court found them correctly and applied them correctly.","start":746.32,"stop":768.397,"duration":22.08},{"text":"The evidence on proportional -- I mean, on discrimination was set out at length in the opinion of the Alabama Supreme Court.","start":768.397,"stop":788.395,"duration":20},{"text":"I would like to set out the evidence at length and came to this conclusion.","start":788.395,"stop":792.505,"duration":4.11},{"text":"I'm reading from page 476 of the record.","start":792.505,"stop":797.293,"duration":4.79},{"text":"A careful consideration of the evidence satisfies us that the great weight of the evidence shows that there was no systematic exclusion of Negroes from the juries in Montgomery County.","start":797.293,"stop":808.455,"duration":11.16},{"text":"We consider that the Court reached a correct conclusion and acted properly in denying the motion to quash the binary.","start":808.455,"stop":816.208,"duration":7.75},{"text":"Now --","start":816.208,"stop":817.478,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":817.478,"stop":820.908,"duration":3.43}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"To the petty jury to the trial jury.","start":820.908,"stop":824.272,"duration":3.36},{"text":"Now, the requirements for jurors in the State of Alabama is found in Section 21 of Title 30 of the 1940 Code of Alabama and I'll brief it just a little bit, but essentially all male citizens of the County who are generally reputed to be honest and intelligent men and are staying in the community for their integrity, good character and sound judgment.","start":824.272,"stop":861.119,"duration":36.85},{"text":"That is the requirement for a juror.","start":861.119,"stop":865.398,"duration":4.28},{"text":"Now, there are some exceptions to that such as they must be over 21.","start":865.398,"stop":869.524,"duration":4.13},{"text":"They cannot be suffering from a permanent disease.","start":869.524,"stop":872.685,"duration":3.16},{"text":"They're illiterate and even there on someone who cannot read, they say if they are a property holder that can -- maybe waived and there are a large number of exemptions from jury duty which is found in Section 3 of Tittle 30.","start":872.685,"stop":889.92,"duration":17.24},{"text":"I don't think they're immaterial so far as this case is concerned.Now, the requirement of Alabama law is that the Board of Jury Supervisors plays or make up a jury list of all citizens of the County which have the requirement, which I have just read.","start":889.92,"stop":913.905,"duration":23.99},{"text":"Then, they make -- found that jury list.","start":913.905,"stop":917.775,"duration":3.87},{"text":"I might say that on the jury list, there is contained the man's name, his occupation, his business address and his residence address and nothing else.","start":917.775,"stop":931.114,"duration":13.34},{"text":"From that jury role, the Clerk of the Board of Jury Supervisors prepares a small white card which contains the man's name, his business or profession, his residence address and his business address and nothing else.","start":931.114,"stop":956.906,"duration":25.79},{"text":"All cards are uniform.","start":956.906,"stop":960.148,"duration":3.24},{"text":"The only other thing on that would be a number which is keyed to the number in the jury role.","start":960.148,"stop":968.748,"duration":8.6}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you have all male jurors?","start":968.748,"stop":970.033,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"All male jurors in the State of Alabama.","start":970.033,"stop":972.494,"duration":2.46},{"text":"It's been a considerable agitation to have women, but it hadn't come about yet.","start":972.494,"stop":977.863,"duration":5.37},{"text":"Those cards are placed in a jury box or a jury wheel, whichever you want to call it.","start":977.863,"stop":984.073,"duration":6.21},{"text":"It's a large metal box.","start":984.073,"stop":987.985,"duration":3.91},{"text":"The judge and the clerk each have keys to that box and it's kept in a vault at all times.","start":987.985,"stop":997.899,"duration":9.91},{"text":"The juries in Montgomery County are all drawn from that box.","start":997.899,"stop":1007.862,"duration":9.96},{"text":"Your petty juries are drawn in open court from that box.","start":1007.862,"stop":1013.091,"duration":5.23},{"text":"Your grand juries are drawn.","start":1013.091,"stop":1014.996,"duration":1.9},{"text":"The names are drawn from that box and both civil and criminal petty juries are drawn from that box.","start":1014.996,"stop":1021.716,"duration":6.72},{"text":"In other words, that's -- that's where we get our juries, the box is brought in open court and the judge will draw for an ordinary -- for a week, 50 names from that box.","start":1021.716,"stop":1035.522,"duration":13.81}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That concerns one division of the --","start":1035.522,"stop":1038.451,"duration":2.93}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- no.","start":1038.451,"stop":1039.417,"duration":0.97},{"text":"That says -- we -- we run an old kind of a time-court.","start":1039.417,"stop":1043.405,"duration":3.99},{"text":"In other words, we have several court, they will draw 50 names for that week.","start":1043.405,"stop":1049.178,"duration":5.77},{"text":"And we'll run civil court for three weeks and then criminal court for three weeks or a month.","start":1049.178,"stop":1054.384,"duration":5.21}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1054.384,"stop":1059.826,"duration":5.44}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"We have two judges, but we draw only one -- one -- 50-man jury.","start":1059.826,"stop":1063.413,"duration":3.59}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And they serve both courts?","start":1063.413,"stop":1065.109,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"They serve both courts, yes, sir","start":1065.109,"stop":1067.381,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, I would like to know as a matter of (Inaudible)","start":1067.381,"stop":1083.921,"duration":16.54}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Eighteen.","start":1083.921,"stop":1085.061,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Does the Court draw more than that and then select from a --","start":1085.061,"stop":1088.007,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it's a double lottery.","start":1088.007,"stop":1089.446,"duration":1.44},{"text":"I was going to get into the -- the method of selection of the grand jury.","start":1089.446,"stop":1093.061,"duration":3.62},{"text":"It -- it's -- you might refer to it as a double lottery.","start":1093.061,"stop":1096.988,"duration":3.93},{"text":"The judge will draw in open court 50 names.","start":1096.988,"stop":1101.537,"duration":4.55},{"text":"Now, they will be subpoenaed, say for two weeks from under two weeks from then to serve as the grand jury.","start":1101.537,"stop":1108.43,"duration":6.89},{"text":"When that day arrives, the -- those jurors who avail and who have not been excused, and I believe the record shows they're ordinarily 35 to 40 who are actually there in Court.","start":1108.43,"stop":1123.949,"duration":15.52},{"text":"Their names are placed on small white slips of paper, just the name.","start":1123.949,"stop":1131.896,"duration":7.95},{"text":"They're placed in a hat and the judge then draws with the handkerchief over it and the judge then draws in open court blind folded, as you might say, 18 names and that constitutes the grand jury.","start":1131.896,"stop":1143.75,"duration":11.85},{"text":"And we have actually four grand juries here.","start":1143.75,"stop":1148.478,"duration":4.73},{"text":"They ordinarily will be for a week and not more than 10 days at a time.","start":1148.478,"stop":1153.753,"duration":5.27},{"text":"Does -- does that answer your question?","start":1153.753,"stop":1155.06,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1155.06,"stop":1156.718,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Approximately how -- approximately how many men names are in that box, the original box from which you draw the --","start":1156.718,"stop":1165.428,"duration":8.71}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"The clerk testified that there are approximately 3000 names.","start":1165.428,"stop":1170.677,"duration":5.25}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Three thousand names in a box?","start":1170.677,"stop":1171.908,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"No, that -- that's in the -- the -- that will be 3000 name serving on juries in Montgomery County.","start":1171.908,"stop":1178.348,"duration":6.44}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1178.348,"stop":1179.791,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Approximately 3000.","start":1179.791,"stop":1182.19,"duration":2.4},{"text":"Now, I've tried to -- to outline the -- the way we draw them because I think it will help -- helpful to you in -- when we get into the testimony as to whether there is -- I might mention this, too.","start":1182.19,"stop":1199.425,"duration":17.23},{"text":"We're talking about grand juries.","start":1199.425,"stop":1202.643,"duration":3.22},{"text":"Now, you're going to find if you read the testimony of all of the witnesses on -- we had a full hearing on systematic exclusion in this case and also in the first case.","start":1202.643,"stop":1214.926,"duration":12.28},{"text":"And you'll find a -- a kind of -- of a hesitation in any of them saying just exactly how many Negroes they've seen on a jury here.","start":1214.926,"stop":1224.23,"duration":9.3},{"text":"How many they've seen there?","start":1224.23,"stop":1225.213,"duration":0.98},{"text":"Now, there's a reason for that.","start":1225.213,"stop":1227.338,"duration":2.13},{"text":"We do not set out juries aside where you can look over here and see that's the jury.","start":1227.338,"stop":1236.317,"duration":8.98},{"text":"Our juries are scattered all over the court room, scattered in with witnesses, spectators and actually, when they draw a grand jury until you actually see the names pulled out of the box and they come up and sit in the box, you wouldn't know who was a juror.","start":1236.317,"stop":1258.335,"duration":22.02},{"text":"You would have no way of knowing it.","start":1258.335,"stop":1259.742,"duration":1.41},{"text":"Absolutely, no way of knowing how many Negroes you had -- who were there as jurors or how many you had spectators or witnesses.","start":1259.742,"stop":1267.733,"duration":7.99},{"text":"Now, we --","start":1267.733,"stop":1267.966,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"We have that in your statement that the choice of a grand jury is truly a matter of -- of a lottery.","start":1267.966,"stop":1273.414,"duration":5.45}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"It is.","start":1273.414,"stop":1274.312,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"There is less choice in the grand jury than there is in a petty jury but --","start":1274.312,"stop":1277.395,"duration":3.08}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"All together -- all together, a grand jury is drawn really by two lots.","start":1277.395,"stop":1281.842,"duration":4.45},{"text":"You draw first your -- your -- the names that are going to be the jury list and then you draw in open court by choice the 18 men who comprise a grand jury.","start":1281.842,"stop":1293.78,"duration":11.94}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Not by choice, but by lot?","start":1293.78,"stop":1295.296,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"By lot, by lot.","start":1295.296,"stop":1296.396,"duration":1.1},{"text":"Yes, the judge has no idea and you'll find in his testimony, he said that he never knows who he is going to draw until he actually opens up the slip and reads the name.","start":1296.396,"stop":1306.797,"duration":10.4},{"text":"Now, the three jury supervisors, three of them testified on the hearing on discrimination.","start":1306.797,"stop":1318.488,"duration":11.69},{"text":"Judge Carter testified.","start":1318.488,"stop":1322.06,"duration":3.57},{"text":"Let me -- let me explain one other thing possibly that might be confusing.","start":1322.06,"stop":1326.658,"duration":4.6},{"text":"We have two-judge Carter's in this case.","start":1326.658,"stop":1328.735,"duration":2.08},{"text":"We have a regular Circuit Judge, is Judge Eugene Carter.","start":1328.735,"stop":1333.135,"duration":4.4},{"text":"When he was subpoenaed as a witness, as he was by the defendant on the hearing on motion to quash the binary, he refused himself and James J.Carter who was a practicing attorney in Montgomery acted as special judge during the trial of this case.","start":1333.135,"stop":1355.502,"duration":22.37}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- about that.","start":1355.502,"stop":1356.721,"duration":1.22},{"text":"There's no complaint of that here?","start":1356.721,"stop":1358.377,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no, complaint here.","start":1358.377,"stop":1359.726,"duration":1.35},{"text":"We've done it on statutory authority.","start":1359.726,"stop":1362.903,"duration":3.18},{"text":"Now, Judge Eugene Carter who testified, testified this.","start":1362.903,"stop":1366.717,"duration":3.81},{"text":"We could hardly pick a jury now without having over four on the jury.","start":1366.717,"stop":1371.341,"duration":4.62},{"text":"I think he was referring that to the binary, not to the actual --","start":1371.341,"stop":1377.047,"duration":5.71}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Panel to try a case.","start":1377.047,"stop":1378.115,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"-- panel to try a case.","start":1378.115,"stop":1380.918,"duration":2.8},{"text":"He had -- he testified further that he had seen seven Negroes sitting on one case, trying a case.","start":1380.918,"stop":1388.386,"duration":7.47},{"text":"He testified that he had seen two Negroes serving on a jury, trying a white man for a robbery.","start":1388.386,"stop":1398.409,"duration":10.02},{"text":"He testified rather at length that he -- that there was no discrimination shown that they were trying to get jurors, not necessarily white jurors or Negro jurors.","start":1398.409,"stop":1410.857,"duration":12.45}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it the theory of how many were actually on the jury trying the case.","start":1410.857,"stop":1415.527,"duration":4.67},{"text":"This is a quick question.","start":1415.527,"stop":1416.83,"duration":1.3},{"text":"How many were on the panel?","start":1416.83,"stop":1418.831,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"That is -- that is true, but we -- but we -- we find that the only way we can show because there's -- there's no designation as Negro or white and about the only way we can show this Court how many -- that -- the Negroes are regular serving on Montgomery County juries.","start":1418.831,"stop":1439.33,"duration":20.5},{"text":"They're in the box in substantial numbers and --","start":1439.33,"stop":1440.907,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is it the question of how many are on the panel rather than the process by which there is a panel selected?","start":1440.907,"stop":1449.542,"duration":8.63},{"text":"Is it a question of numbers or process?","start":1449.542,"stop":1451.267,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't -- I think counsel says that it is not a question of numbers.","start":1451.267,"stop":1456.677,"duration":5.41},{"text":"It's a question where they're discriminated against.","start":1456.677,"stop":1458.54,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it --","start":1458.54,"stop":1458.988,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"But the only we can -- we can get at that is kind of going in the backdoor to show you that they're on -- on the case.","start":1458.988,"stop":1465.394,"duration":6.41},{"text":"I --","start":1465.394,"stop":1465.77,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand of course if no Negroes ever on the panel and you've got a sizeable Negro population, a potential body of jurors and if there never is a colored person on the panel, that's an awfully good piece of evidence that there's something that matter with the process.","start":1465.77,"stop":1487.479,"duration":21.71},{"text":"But the mere fact that there is one or two as against some other proportion of white, doesn't prove that there is discrimination, is it there?","start":1487.479,"stop":1499.24,"duration":11.76}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Now we're trying to prove that it was not discrimination.","start":1499.24,"stop":1501.028,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but -- but is it -- I'll go back to my question.","start":1501.028,"stop":1504.755,"duration":3.73},{"text":"Is it a question of numbers if the fact there were three or four, does that settle it?","start":1504.755,"stop":1509.987,"duration":5.23},{"text":"And if there's only one, it settles it the other way?","start":1509.987,"stop":1512.924,"duration":2.94},{"text":"Do you concede that's to be the problem?","start":1512.924,"stop":1515.337,"duration":2.41},{"text":"Except there's evidentiary fact --","start":1515.337,"stop":1517.121,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Except there's evidentiary fact, that would --","start":1517.121,"stop":1518.836,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- these numbers because this Court has held that it doesn't require to have a proportion.","start":1518.836,"stop":1524.182,"duration":5.35}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that's exactly what I'm arguing.","start":1524.182,"stop":1525.641,"duration":1.46},{"text":"I'm trying to get to this Court the fact that we have Negro serving as a matter of cause everyday and I think the record bears that statement after.","start":1525.641,"stop":1536.389,"duration":10.75}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't think the observation that I had in mind quite clear is this (Inaudible) what you mean by panel.","start":1536.389,"stop":1547.619,"duration":11.23},{"text":"To me, the panel is the final 12 sworn to try a lawsuit.","start":1547.619,"stop":1555.114,"duration":7.5},{"text":"Now, the fact that there are no Negroes on that jury, doesn't mean that in the process of selection from the binary, there may not have been six restricken on each side for cause or peremptorily, isn't that true?","start":1555.114,"stop":1571.859,"duration":16.74}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- that's very true.","start":1571.859,"stop":1574.547,"duration":2.69},{"text":"But we feel that the -- a large measure -- the only way we can show you that they are on the binary which is the entire 50 men or 100 men group, is to show you that they're actually serving on juries which they are.","start":1574.547,"stop":1588.252,"duration":13.7}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what?","start":1588.252,"stop":1589.112,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- I say, we feel that the best way that we've got -- and as a matter of fact, the only way we've got because as I told you, your juries are so mixed-in with spectators and with witnesses that ordinarily no one knows who's the jury and who's not.","start":1589.112,"stop":1605.998,"duration":16.89},{"text":"We -- and we've got no designation on anything that would show a man was white or a man was colored.","start":1605.998,"stop":1612.635,"duration":6.64}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But the fact that even on the panel, you are regularly always two Negroes wouldn't disprove discrimination.","start":1612.635,"stop":1620.85,"duration":8.21}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we don't -- we -- the evidence in this shows that we have varying numbers of Negroes.","start":1620.85,"stop":1626.033,"duration":5.18}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm not -- I'm not talking to the specific things.","start":1626.033,"stop":1628.73,"duration":2.7},{"text":"I'm trying to get the standard, the criteria, the basis on which judgment must be made, not the particular facts.","start":1628.73,"stop":1637.16,"duration":8.43}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the -- the evidence in this case, the evidence that was that is in this record shows this that we have as sometimes a fair large number of Negro serving on the juries, sometimes no Negroes at all.","start":1637.16,"stop":1653.785,"duration":16.63},{"text":"We have -- the evidence shows that the witness has testified they had seen as many as five serving on petty juries on several occasions.","start":1653.785,"stop":1666.09,"duration":12.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"We're here on the grand -- aren't we concerned with the grand jury panel?","start":1666.09,"stop":1669.958,"duration":3.87}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't know if we or not but the evidence in the State's contention that we are not, but the --","start":1669.958,"stop":1676.73,"duration":6.77}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but the claim is --","start":1676.73,"stop":1678.02,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"The claim -- well --","start":1678.02,"stop":1679.6,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- man compared because --","start":1679.6,"stop":1680.1,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Now you -- you --","start":1680.1,"stop":1681.193,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it's issued from a discriminating jury.","start":1681.193,"stop":1684.147,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"You will -- you will find in the record.","start":1684.147,"stop":1687.404,"duration":3.26},{"text":"In the testimony, I testified in the case, a -- and my testimony was to the effect that in over half of the grand jury since 1951, there had been one or more Negro serving actually on the grand jury.","start":1687.404,"stop":1707.774,"duration":20.37},{"text":"Now, that --","start":1707.774,"stop":1708.48,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Did Mr. Hall -- did I hear Mr. Hall correct me to say that it is Judge Carter's testimony that in -- I forget what.","start":1708.48,"stop":1718.449,"duration":9.97},{"text":"In the course of 20, 19 years whatever it was, he'd seen only one colored man on the grand jury or during that whole period.","start":1718.449,"stop":1727.047,"duration":8.6}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"As I read it.","start":1727.047,"stop":1727.439,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't that what Mr. Hall said?","start":1727.439,"stop":1728.654,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that's what he said, but as I read --","start":1728.654,"stop":1729.99,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now is that true?","start":1729.99,"stop":1731.71,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it's not -- that's not true.","start":1731.71,"stop":1733.892,"duration":2.18},{"text":"You will find a testimony of a good many of the witnesses in there that they have seen varying numbers of Negroes, actually serving on the grand jury of one, two, three and four.","start":1733.892,"stop":1743.856,"duration":9.96},{"text":"There's no testimony of all the four in there.","start":1743.856,"stop":1746.219,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, did Judge Carter testify --","start":1746.219,"stop":1748.265,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Judge Carter said that he couldn't remember.","start":1748.265,"stop":1750.654,"duration":2.39},{"text":"He wouldn't -- he would not commit himself.","start":1750.654,"stop":1752.232,"duration":1.58},{"text":"He said he could remember one man -- one Negro serving.","start":1752.232,"stop":1754.889,"duration":2.66},{"text":"He remembered his name, but he would not testify further.","start":1754.889,"stop":1756.06,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you -- are you saying that he did not testified that in those 20 years, whatever it was, there was only one?","start":1756.06,"stop":1762.276,"duration":6.22}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm saying he did not testify that.","start":1762.276,"stop":1764.814,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let me ask you on that.","start":1764.814,"stop":1766.571,"duration":1.76},{"text":"How would one know who was on the grand jury in the -- as a general proposition cannot convene privately?","start":1766.571,"stop":1777.688,"duration":11.12},{"text":"They're not in -- they're only in court when they're selected and when they returned indictment.","start":1777.688,"stop":1782.222,"duration":4.53}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"That is true, but the grand jury in Montgomery County ordinarily, the makeup of the grand jury as published in the paper and because you would see them as they're convinced.You would see him going back and forward.","start":1782.222,"stop":1791.833,"duration":9.61},{"text":"Now, the judge would see him only when he charges him and when they report in, because I was in a little better position to testify on that because I work with the grand jury as long as I have ever been.","start":1791.833,"stop":1802.114,"duration":10.28}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Only one judge is there?","start":1802.114,"stop":1803.701,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Two.","start":1803.701,"stop":1805.314,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1805.314,"stop":1808.31,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"He is the presiding judge of the Criminal Court and would have seem, Judge Jones occasionally charges the grand jury, but not all of them.","start":1808.31,"stop":1819.084,"duration":10.77},{"text":"Actually, I will get through the grand jury.","start":1819.084,"stop":1821.76,"duration":2.68},{"text":"As I say, we had -- I had a -- I pointed out that we get our grand jury list and now petty jury list from the same box.","start":1821.76,"stop":1832.455,"duration":10.69},{"text":"There's no -- no distinction.","start":1832.455,"stop":1833.687,"duration":1.23},{"text":"They would come from the same box.","start":1833.687,"stop":1836.734,"duration":3.05},{"text":"And whatever the evidence is as to -- the petty jury would also be as to the grand jury, because it comes from the same box.","start":1836.734,"stop":1851.664,"duration":14.93},{"text":"I think that the State showed in the hearing in 1955 that we will not discriminate against anybody, that they were looking for jurors.","start":1851.664,"stop":1864.124,"duration":12.46},{"text":"There were certainly no evidence and no jurors (Inaudible) token service by Negroes in Montgomery County.","start":1864.124,"stop":1873.773,"duration":9.65}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What's the evidence as to the sources from which the names are examined?","start":1873.773,"stop":1880.41,"duration":6.64}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"They -- the Board of Jury Supervisors testified that they consulted -- are you speaking of Negro or Negro and white?","start":1880.41,"stop":1889.875,"duration":9.46}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, just generally, I --","start":1889.875,"stop":1891.134,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Just generally, they -- they consulted civic clubs.","start":1891.134,"stop":1894.735,"duration":3.6},{"text":"They testified.","start":1894.735,"stop":1895.503,"duration":0.77},{"text":"They had consulted NAACP, the old Civic (Inaudible) Association of a Negro organization that they had consulted a good many of the Negro leaders in Montgomery asking for a list of -- of Negroes who met the qualifications for jury duty that are have good -- good, honest, intelligent --","start":1895.503,"stop":1920.05,"duration":24.55}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And is it a -- a similar procedure including white names?","start":1920.05,"stop":1922.374,"duration":2.32}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Similar procedure -- similar procedure with the white.","start":1922.374,"stop":1925.913,"duration":3.54},{"text":"They consult -- now, you have to understand this.","start":1925.913,"stop":1929.126,"duration":3.21},{"text":"In Montgomery, we have a good many white organizations that have no comparable Negro.","start":1929.126,"stop":1938.456,"duration":9.33},{"text":"In other words, as Montgomery Kiwanis Club, it's white.","start":1938.456,"stop":1941.038,"duration":2.58},{"text":"There is no Negro Kiwanis Club.","start":1941.038,"stop":1943.945,"duration":2.91},{"text":"We have to go to possibly other sources, but they would be equal sources and that was their testimony that they consulted these both individuals and societies and associations --","start":1943.945,"stop":1956.058,"duration":12.11}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Was there any reliance on voting lists or other public lists of that kind?","start":1956.058,"stop":1960.178,"duration":4.12}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1960.178,"stop":1961.542,"duration":1.36},{"text":"I believe there is testimony from one of the jury commissioners that he had gotten the -- the voting -- well, of course they'll probably look at the voting list anyhow, that he had gotten Negroes to go down the whole list and pick out before him people that they could say, were honest and straight to -- to place in the jury box.","start":1961.542,"stop":1980.562,"duration":19.02}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"How often are those lists assembled?","start":1980.562,"stop":1982.959,"duration":2.4},{"text":"Are they done periodically or annually or something?","start":1982.959,"stop":1985.644,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"They are revised once a year --","start":1985.644,"stop":1987.349,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Once a year.","start":1987.349,"stop":1987.576,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"-- by law.","start":1987.576,"stop":1988.916,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Thetford, what educational institutions other -- other than primary schools are there in Montgomery to which Negroes have access?","start":1988.916,"stop":2000.378,"duration":11.46}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"We have the Alabama State Normal College in Montgomery.","start":2000.378,"stop":2002.908,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In Montgomery.","start":2002.908,"stop":2003.511,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"In Montgomery.","start":2003.511,"stop":2004.142,"duration":0.63},{"text":"It's a Negro college.","start":2004.142,"stop":2004.812,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And that has sizeable Negro faculties?","start":2004.812,"stop":2008.488,"duration":3.68}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it does.","start":2008.488,"stop":2010.442,"duration":1.95},{"text":"And we also have -- well, Kostowski is not in Montgomery County.","start":2010.442,"stop":2014.266,"duration":3.82}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm -- it's a principal question, but I would call in the State (Inaudible) is he consulted as one of the people who -- he would know --","start":2014.266,"stop":2021.811,"duration":7.54}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"You will find in the record that a teacher by the name of (Inaudible) at State Normal, furnished Mr. Mathews who is Clerk of the Board, a list of -- from 30 to 50 names which Mr. Mathews said all of them were placed in the box.","start":2021.811,"stop":2041.169,"duration":19.36}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"How many Negro lawyers in Montgomery?","start":2041.169,"stop":2042.933,"duration":1.76}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Two.","start":2042.933,"stop":2043.737,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Two, Negro doctors?","start":2043.737,"stop":2046.48,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Several.","start":2046.48,"stop":2047.482,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Dentist?","start":2047.482,"stop":2049.107,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"There's more than one.","start":2049.107,"stop":2051.335,"duration":2.23}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"There is a professional --","start":2051.335,"stop":2052.71,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"There is a professional group of -- of course we are possibly tied down because your better educated Negro almost always is a professional man in Montgomery.","start":2052.71,"stop":2062.83,"duration":10.12}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So -- and he's excused.","start":2062.83,"stop":2064.123,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"And he is excused.","start":2064.123,"stop":2065.339,"duration":1.22},{"text":"So, we have that problem.","start":2065.339,"stop":2067.068,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Businessmen?","start":2067.068,"stop":2068.699,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"We have businessmen, we --","start":2068.699,"stop":2070.036,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"How many of -- some inside?","start":2070.036,"stop":2072.927,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, we -- we have businessmen of importance in Montgomery and they serve on juries too.","start":2072.927,"stop":2081.245,"duration":8.32}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Do they got a Negro architect by any chance?","start":2081.245,"stop":2083.208,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no, sir.","start":2083.208,"stop":2084.871,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Referring to your list of 3000 that are in the box, is there any testimony of any kind that indicates the proportion of those of white or colored?","start":2084.871,"stop":2093.107,"duration":8.24}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":2093.107,"stop":2093.871,"duration":0.76},{"text":"There isn't and it would be impossible to tell because there is no designation as to white or designation as to colored.","start":2093.871,"stop":2100.582,"duration":6.71}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It will be better if there were, wasn't it?","start":2100.582,"stop":2102.675,"duration":2.09},{"text":"We -- it's indicated --","start":2102.675,"stop":2104.005,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"This -- this Court has said we can so designate them.","start":2104.005,"stop":2108.551,"duration":4.55}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Thetford, about what is the population of that County, Montgomery County?","start":2108.551,"stop":2114.581,"duration":6.03}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"140,000, I believe.","start":2114.581,"stop":2116.402,"duration":1.82},{"text":"It's in that neighborhood.","start":2116.402,"stop":2119.782,"duration":3.38}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) that were called for service (Voice Overlap) on the panel and subjected to the Board for examination.","start":2119.782,"stop":2140.59,"duration":20.81}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"We have very little examination.","start":2140.59,"stop":2145.588,"duration":5},{"text":"You're speaking of petty juries now?","start":2145.588,"stop":2147.545,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, you've (Inaudible) haven't you?","start":2147.545,"stop":2151.71,"duration":4.16}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":2151.71,"stop":2152.085,"duration":0.38},{"text":"We don't get our jurist on that -- on that basis.","start":2152.085,"stop":2154.443,"duration":2.36},{"text":"The jury -- our juries are selected in this manner.","start":2154.443,"stop":2161.15,"duration":6.71},{"text":"If they are, say a 35 --","start":2161.15,"stop":2164.623,"duration":3.47}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Present.","start":2164.623,"stop":2165.076,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Present.","start":2165.076,"stop":2168.926,"duration":3.85},{"text":"The defendant -- no, state strikes first.","start":2168.926,"stop":2173.1,"duration":4.17},{"text":"The defendant strikes two.","start":2173.1,"stop":2175.041,"duration":1.94},{"text":"The State strikes one.","start":2175.041,"stop":2176.124,"duration":1.08},{"text":"The defendant strikes two until we have 12 names left and that is the jurist revocation.","start":2176.124,"stop":2180.893,"duration":4.77}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Out of the whole 35?","start":2180.893,"stop":2182.001,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Out of the whole 35.","start":2182.001,"stop":2182.913,"duration":0.91},{"text":"The whole 35 might well be used.","start":2182.913,"stop":2185.398,"duration":2.49},{"text":"The law requires -- Alabama procedure requires at least 24.","start":2185.398,"stop":2190.498,"duration":5.1},{"text":"The jurors will be there for a non-capital case and 30, a capital case.","start":2190.498,"stop":2195.861,"duration":5.36}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"There is no board wide examination?","start":2195.861,"stop":2198.957,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"We -- we have the right.Both state of all parties have the right to examine jurors on any particular thing if they so desire.","start":2198.957,"stop":2211.742,"duration":12.79}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) not the judge.","start":2211.742,"stop":2213.415,"duration":1.67}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"The judge does it at the request of the lawyers.","start":2213.415,"stop":2215.339,"duration":1.92},{"text":"It's done on supervision of the Court and ordinarily the judge -- we ask him to ask the questions and he asked the questions of the jurors.","start":2215.339,"stop":2223.604,"duration":8.26}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"That's of the whole 35 or more -- if there are more present.","start":2223.604,"stop":2227.4,"duration":3.8}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, sir.","start":2227.4,"stop":2230.541,"duration":3.14}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2230.541,"stop":2236.595,"duration":6.05}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2236.595,"stop":2238.495,"duration":1.9},{"text":"I want to make one more observation then I'm -- I'm leaving this.","start":2238.495,"stop":2244.216,"duration":5.72},{"text":"In 1954, when the first Jeremiah Reeves case came before this Court, this same proposition of systematic exclusion of Negroes from grand juries of Montgomery County was both briefed and argued before this Court.","start":2244.216,"stop":2265.85,"duration":21.63},{"text":"The Court at that time seems satisfied with our method of selecting jurors and seems satisfied that there was no discrimination being shown, Negroes, in Montgomery County.","start":2265.85,"stop":2280.774,"duration":14.92},{"text":"The case was not reversed on systematic exclusion.","start":2280.774,"stop":2283.42,"duration":2.65},{"text":"It was reversed on the remarks and the nature of a confession.","start":2283.42,"stop":2289.931,"duration":6.51},{"text":"And I submit to the Court that it -- just as you are pointing out, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, it -- cases should not be and they have the right to do it, and you have the right to do it, but cases -- criminal cases should not be reversed piecemeal.","start":2289.931,"stop":2308.256,"duration":18.32},{"text":"We of course are bound by it and will follow the dictates of this Court, but when the case comes up here and it's reversed on a confession, obviously, we think the jury's proposition has been argued, briefed to, and no mention of it, is made in this Court's opinion.","start":2308.256,"stop":2328.092,"duration":19.84}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the difference in the record on this discrimination question and the present record as to -- as compared with the one we had before us in 1954?","start":2328.092,"stop":2337.662,"duration":9.57}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"We have a much fuller record on this case than we did in the 1954.","start":2337.662,"stop":2346.05,"duration":8.39},{"text":"The --","start":2346.05,"stop":2346.322,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And the full of means what is bearing on wether there is a reason of discrimination.","start":2346.322,"stop":2350.26,"duration":3.94}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think it's directed from the State's standpoint.","start":2350.26,"stop":2353.178,"duration":2.92},{"text":"It -- a great many more people testified.","start":2353.178,"stop":2355.555,"duration":2.38},{"text":"We haven't in there a large number of lawyers testified that they had tried cases with Negro jurors.","start":2355.555,"stop":2361.435,"duration":5.88},{"text":"Now, this is in the -- the present record.","start":2361.435,"stop":2363.89,"duration":2.45},{"text":"In the first record, we have only the three witnesses testified and they testified simply that Negroes were serving on the juries, both grand jury and petty jury.","start":2363.89,"stop":2380.021,"duration":16.13},{"text":"The next question that I would like to talk about is the reindictment and rearraignment of the defendant in -- the defendant was neither reindicted nor rearraigned after the first reversal.","start":2380.021,"stop":2398.339,"duration":18.32},{"text":"That is standard -- that is Alabama procedure.","start":2398.339,"stop":2402.165,"duration":3.83},{"text":"There is no requirement for a reindictment.","start":2402.165,"stop":2405.128,"duration":2.96},{"text":"No requirement for a rearraignment.","start":2405.128,"stop":2408.87,"duration":3.74},{"text":"The -- as a matter of fact, Alabama, I think follows a majority of the states in that.","start":2408.87,"stop":2414.857,"duration":5.99},{"text":"There are number of various jurisdictions which are cited where Alabama has a limitation on that if your indictment is amended or the man is acquitted of a higher offense by being convicted of a law then better practices to reindict, but we don't require it.","start":2414.857,"stop":2434.586,"duration":19.73},{"text":"And the --","start":2434.586,"stop":2434.868,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you saying -- are you saying that if cases go up from the trial court to your Supreme Court, and your Supreme Court reverses for error in the admission of evidence for erroneous charge or anyone of the grounds on which a state court can and your Supreme Court does reversed, you've got a good many reversals over the years unfortunately.","start":2434.868,"stop":2458.14,"duration":23.27},{"text":"When it goes back, you -- you continue it as what -- as though -- as those what, still part of the original indictment and arraignment, is that right?","start":2458.14,"stop":2466.386,"duration":8.25}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2466.386,"stop":2467.569,"duration":1.18},{"text":"That as I say is done in -- in most jurisdictions, I believe.","start":2467.569,"stop":2472.354,"duration":4.78}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Can I ask you a question about the 1952 challenge with the grand jury?","start":2472.354,"stop":2476.35,"duration":4},{"text":"Did he have a hearing as I read the Court's opinion here?","start":2476.35,"stop":2479.212,"duration":2.86},{"text":"There was a hearing at that time.","start":2479.212,"stop":2480.439,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"There was not -- Judge (Inaudible) in his opinion, I'll have to admit was in error.","start":2480.439,"stop":2486.267,"duration":5.83},{"text":"There was no hearing on the motion on the --","start":2486.267,"stop":2489.173,"duration":2.91}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"1952 challenge","start":2489.173,"stop":2489.843,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"In 1952 challenge.","start":2489.843,"stop":2490.912,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That statement is raised.","start":2490.912,"stop":2492.227,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"I won't cover that.","start":2492.227,"stop":2495.196,"duration":2.97},{"text":"I simply point out to the Court that petitioner makes a point that -- that he should have been reindicted and rearraigned in -- in this case because there was no mandate from this Court.","start":2495.196,"stop":2510.085,"duration":14.89},{"text":"It was simply reversed.","start":2510.085,"stop":2511.067,"duration":0.98},{"text":"That of course is not correct.","start":2511.067,"stop":2513.674,"duration":2.61},{"text":"The waiting of this Court's judgment reversed the case to the Supreme Court of Alabama for proceedings not inconsistent with the opinion of this Court.","start":2513.674,"stop":2524.694,"duration":11.02},{"text":"See, Kennedy versus Alabama and (Inaudible) versus Alabama.","start":2524.694,"stop":2528.512,"duration":3.82}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Thetford, is there a statute of limitations on this crime?","start":2528.512,"stop":2533.282,"duration":4.77}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"On the Alabama practice, there is no statute of limitation on any capital offense.","start":2533.282,"stop":2541.699,"duration":8.42},{"text":"Now, the defendant in getting to the grand -- to the challenge to the grand jury in 1952, the defendant was arrested on November 10th.","start":2541.699,"stop":2551.57,"duration":9.87},{"text":"He was arraigned on November 4th -- indicted on November the 14th.","start":2551.57,"stop":2555.88,"duration":4.31},{"text":"He was arraigned on November the 15th.","start":2555.88,"stop":2558.725,"duration":2.84},{"text":"At the time of he -- his arraignment, he was represented by counsel of his own choice, counsel that petitioner now freely admits was competent and capable and exerted every effort in his behalf.","start":2558.725,"stop":2576.422,"duration":17.7},{"text":"On the 15th when he was arraigned, the -- Mr. (Inaudible) who then represented petitioner asked for a continuance of the arraignment.","start":2576.422,"stop":2586.468,"duration":10.05},{"text":"He stated no grounds for that continuance.","start":2586.468,"stop":2589.888,"duration":3.42},{"text":"He simply -- as we find in the practice of criminal law, a great many continuances are requested.","start":2589.888,"stop":2597.915,"duration":8.03},{"text":"He subsequently requested a continuance of the trial.","start":2597.915,"stop":2600.879,"duration":2.96},{"text":"It's -- when -- then on -- now, Alabama practice requires that a -- requires that an indictment be attacked by plea in abatement which must be filed before a plea to the merits.","start":2600.879,"stop":2619.08,"duration":18.2},{"text":"Now, on the 15th, when he was arraigned, there was no plea made to the merits.","start":2619.08,"stop":2626.739,"duration":7.66}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"None was made that day?","start":2626.739,"stop":2627.847,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"None was made that day.","start":2627.847,"stop":2629.86,"duration":2.01},{"text":"The plea -- wait a minute.","start":2629.86,"stop":2632.218,"duration":2.36},{"text":"I'm misstating that.","start":2632.218,"stop":2633.335,"duration":1.12},{"text":"There was no objection taken to the indictment.","start":2633.335,"stop":2639.835,"duration":6.5},{"text":"There was no motion filed to quash on arraignment.","start":2639.835,"stop":2642.562,"duration":2.73},{"text":"He would simply --","start":2642.562,"stop":2642.966,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"But he -- but he did pleaded.","start":2642.966,"stop":2644.718,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"He pled not guilty and not guilty by reason of insanity.","start":2644.718,"stop":2649.354,"duration":4.64},{"text":"Now --","start":2649.354,"stop":2649.567,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that the day on which he asked for a continuance?","start":2649.567,"stop":2652.033,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"He asked for a continuance without stating grounds for it and he subsequently -- and then when that was overruled, he pled not guilty and not guilty by reason of insanity.","start":2652.033,"stop":2663.231,"duration":11.2},{"text":"On --","start":2663.231,"stop":2663.475,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Thetford, did I misunderstand Mr. Hall?","start":2663.475,"stop":2665.541,"duration":2.07},{"text":"I thought I heard him say that he asked the continuance in order that he might make a motion to attack the indictment.","start":2665.541,"stop":2673.435,"duration":7.89}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- you will not find that in the record.","start":2673.435,"stop":2676.11,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"There is a record of what occurred at --","start":2676.11,"stop":2677.76,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"There is a record.","start":2677.76,"stop":2678.451,"duration":0.69},{"text":"He simply made a motion for a continuance.","start":2678.451,"stop":2680.448,"duration":2},{"text":"He stated no grounds for it.","start":2680.448,"stop":2683.374,"duration":2.93},{"text":"On the 26th, when this case came for trial, he then filed a motion to quash the indictment alleging systematic exclusion of Negroes from the grand jury.","start":2683.374,"stop":2694.688,"duration":11.31},{"text":"Now, that was 11 days after he was arraigned.","start":2694.688,"stop":2701.653,"duration":6.96},{"text":"That motion was overruled and then he filed a motion to quash the binary which really gave him exactly the same thing because our -- our grand jury and trial binary are taken from the same box.","start":2701.653,"stop":2714.503,"duration":12.85},{"text":"Now, he abandoned the motion to quash the indictment.","start":2714.503,"stop":2723.505,"duration":9},{"text":"He did not argue that before the Supreme Court of Alabama on his subsequent appeal.","start":2723.505,"stop":2727.674,"duration":4.17},{"text":"He -- it was neither briefed it and argued before this case in 1954.","start":2727.674,"stop":2732.831,"duration":5.16},{"text":"We meet again in 1955 when we again go to trial with this defendant, and they then asked that they'd be allowed to withdraw their pleas to the merits filed on November the 15th, 1952.","start":2732.831,"stop":2751.1,"duration":18.27},{"text":"The State asked grounds that they've got different lawyers and that they would like to test the constitutionality of the -- of constitutional questions in regard to grand jury which the -- actually, the motion that we are now considering was filed two and a half years after arraignment.","start":2751.1,"stop":2772.936,"duration":21.84},{"text":"Now, the -- he had his opportunity.","start":2772.936,"stop":2777.109,"duration":4.17},{"text":"I -- I will point this out to the Court that there is a relatively short time between the time Mr. (Inaudible) was hired.","start":2777.109,"stop":2785.491,"duration":8.38},{"text":"I don't know when he was hired, but it was a day or so before the arraignment of Jeremiah Reeves.","start":2785.491,"stop":2792.197,"duration":6.71},{"text":"Now, on the Alabama practice, a one paragraph pleading would have been sufficient on a motion to quash the indictment.","start":2792.197,"stop":2803.477,"duration":11.28},{"text":"He could have.","start":2803.477,"stop":2804.645,"duration":1.17},{"text":"There was no insuperable barrier to keep him as -- as in (Inaudible) case.","start":2804.645,"stop":2811.923,"duration":7.28},{"text":"There was nothing to keep him if he had wanted to from filing that plea in abatement.","start":2811.923,"stop":2817.403,"duration":5.48}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, would he have been obliged to proceed there at that -- at that moment?","start":2817.403,"stop":2822.086,"duration":4.68}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":2822.086,"stop":2822.8,"duration":0.71},{"text":"No, no, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":2822.8,"stop":2824.194,"duration":1.39},{"text":"What would have happened then was witnesses would have been -- the -- the whole idea is an orderly carrying forward of justice.","start":2824.194,"stop":2833.342,"duration":9.15},{"text":"They -- the law tries to get these preliminary matters out of the way before you actually, your juries and your witnesses are subpoenaed to -- to try the case.","start":2833.342,"stop":2844.026,"duration":10.68},{"text":"It would have been set in the usual course of our procedure some time during the next week or so.","start":2844.026,"stop":2849.354,"duration":5.33},{"text":"We had 11 days before the case was actually tried.","start":2849.354,"stop":2853.161,"duration":3.81}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"In which time he would have enough to litigate his witnesses on his motion to quash?","start":2853.161,"stop":2857.425,"duration":4.26}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2857.425,"stop":2858.514,"duration":1.09},{"text":"Now, that's what as I say was not filed under the case.","start":2858.514,"stop":2860.661,"duration":2.15},{"text":"Actually, it was called for a trial on the 26.","start":2860.661,"stop":2863.564,"duration":2.9}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"When the -- when did the case get back to you for trial after we got (Inaudible)?","start":2863.564,"stop":2868.85,"duration":5.29}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"This case was reversed in December 1955 and we tried him again in May.","start":2868.85,"stop":2872.846,"duration":4}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, that's 1954?","start":2872.846,"stop":2874.323,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"1954.","start":2874.323,"stop":2875.645,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And you tried him in May?","start":2875.645,"stop":2877.815,"duration":2.17},{"text":"Did you try him in May 1955?","start":2877.815,"stop":2879.918,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2879.918,"stop":2880.202,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And you got a verdict in May?","start":2880.202,"stop":2881.777,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- yes, sir.","start":2881.777,"stop":2882.561,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And when did it get to the Supreme Court of Alabama?","start":2882.561,"stop":2886.729,"duration":4.17},{"text":"The next year, isn't it?","start":2886.729,"stop":2887.8,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"The next year, yes, sir.","start":2887.8,"stop":2888.706,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that because of the (Inaudible), I mean, the business of your course?","start":2888.706,"stop":2895.889,"duration":7.18}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Frankfurter, we find the Supreme Court of Alabama is -- is pretty slow in deciding cases for sometimes a year or so.","start":2895.889,"stop":2902.802,"duration":6.91}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"After it's submitted.","start":2902.802,"stop":2904.092,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"After it's -- after the trial.","start":2904.092,"stop":2906.448,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"They have a heavy (Inaudible) about it --","start":2906.448,"stop":2907.847,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir, they have.","start":2907.847,"stop":2911.694,"duration":3.85}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"My question is derived from my greatest (Inaudible) delayed does not meant criticism to you.","start":2911.694,"stop":2916.985,"duration":5.29},{"text":"This is true to our country.","start":2916.985,"stop":2920.172,"duration":3.19}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm -- I'm going to take no more time.","start":2920.172,"stop":2923.003,"duration":2.83},{"text":"We have one other problem of the refusal of the trial court to let the -- as to evidence before the -- as to where there was evidence before the grand -- grand jury, legally before the grand jury.","start":2923.003,"stop":2942.218,"duration":19.21},{"text":"I don't think that's much of a problem.","start":2942.218,"stop":2944.034,"duration":1.82},{"text":"I think that Costello answers it as far as the Federal Court is concerned and certainly our cases, hold that they have no right to inquire into what evidence was submitted to the grand jury and I'm not going to argue that, and I want to give Mr. Stewart --","start":2944.034,"stop":2958.141,"duration":14.11}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Could I ask you one question to clear my mind?","start":2958.141,"stop":2960.172,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2960.172,"stop":2961.402,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you say that he did not press in the Alabama Supreme Court his denial of his motion to quash the grand jury?","start":2961.402,"stop":2970.802,"duration":9.4}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":2970.802,"stop":2971.919,"duration":1.12},{"text":"That was apparently abandoned.","start":2971.919,"stop":2974.001,"duration":2.08},{"text":"It was not --","start":2974.001,"stop":2974.697,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But then did he press -- did he seek to press it up here (Voice Overlap)?","start":2974.697,"stop":2977.588,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":2977.588,"stop":2978.041,"duration":0.45},{"text":"It was neither briefed nor argued nor urged on this Court in 19 -- in 1954,","start":2978.041,"stop":2983.491,"duration":5.45}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It was not?","start":2983.491,"stop":2984.176,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":2984.176,"stop":2985.523,"duration":1.35},{"text":"It was completely abandoned and did not come back again until the new trial in May of 1955.","start":2985.523,"stop":2992.335,"duration":6.81}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I misunderstood something that you said earlier then because I thought you would argue that although the Court here did not pass on the grand jury question in 1954 and they had an opportunity to do so and therefore, you could assume that the (Inaudible) --","start":2992.335,"stop":3008.863,"duration":16.53}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"What I said was that the same exact proposition was submitted in the attack on the petty jury, because the juries are drawn out of the same box.","start":3008.863,"stop":3018.936,"duration":10.07}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What petty jury?","start":3018.936,"stop":3020.746,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"William F. Thetford","textObjs":[{"text":"It would be the same jury.","start":3020.746,"stop":3022.217,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3022.217,"stop":3027.893,"duration":5.68}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Stewart.","start":3027.893,"stop":3028.889,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Robert B. Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":3028.889,"stop":3031.89,"duration":3},{"text":"I have planned about 20 plus -- 30-minute talk.","start":3031.89,"stop":3035.762,"duration":3.87},{"text":"I'll see if I could compress that into five minutes that I have remaining.","start":3035.762,"stop":3040.657,"duration":4.89},{"text":"There were several points briefed which I would like to talk to, but I would try to limit it to one point only in the time that I have and that is the oral examination of the jurors.","start":3040.657,"stop":3057.946,"duration":17.29},{"text":"The defendant has raised a point about a question as to all jurors.","start":3057.946,"stop":3064.857,"duration":6.91},{"text":"The Solicitor asked the Court to qualify the jurors as to membership in the NAACP.","start":3064.857,"stop":3074.747,"duration":9.89},{"text":"Now, the defendant at that time objected to that question being asked to jurors.","start":3074.747,"stop":3083.429,"duration":8.68},{"text":"The Solicitor then stated that it was his information that the NAACP was financing this case and he would like that information to be helpful to him in striking the jury.","start":3083.429,"stop":3096.518,"duration":13.09},{"text":"Of course --","start":3096.518,"stop":3098.409,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that --","start":3098.409,"stop":3099.545,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Robert B. Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":3099.545,"stop":3100.801,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"That said is openly in the presence of hearing of all (Inaudible)?","start":3100.801,"stop":3107.31,"duration":6.51}]},{"speakerName":"Robert B. Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Openly in the presence of all jurors, yes sir, because all jurors are sitting in the court room.","start":3107.31,"stop":3112,"duration":4.69}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3112,"stop":3120.158,"duration":8.16}]},{"speakerName":"Robert B. Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3120.158,"stop":3120.827,"duration":0.67},{"text":"Now that was not said until objection was made to the question that they'd be qualified as to membership.","start":3120.827,"stop":3127.431,"duration":6.6},{"text":"Now, that -- that belief of course comes to us from the fact that the name of the chief counsel, general counsel of NAACP appears on the last brief in this Court.","start":3127.431,"stop":3139.99,"duration":12.56},{"text":"That's our understanding from the record.","start":3139.99,"stop":3145.302,"duration":5.31},{"text":"And to prove that it was a useful question, I point out to you that the record shows three of the jurors when they were so qualified, stated that they were members of the NAACP.","start":3145.302,"stop":3158.713,"duration":13.41},{"text":"Now --","start":3158.713,"stop":3159.04,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"-- practice even in the civil case, I assume we have issues arising as to whether or not jurors made to examine the negligence cases as to whether the defendant has or doesn't have insurance.","start":3159.04,"stop":3174.905,"duration":15.87}]},{"speakerName":"Robert B. Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3174.905,"stop":3175.339,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you permitted to ask such broader questions upon an understanding or do you not have to have some admission if you use such insurance before you're permitted to ask the question?","start":3175.339,"stop":3187.989,"duration":12.65}]},{"speakerName":"Robert B. Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":3187.989,"stop":3188.37,"duration":0.38},{"text":"You may -- you may ask the question upon your own understanding.","start":3188.37,"stop":3191.78,"duration":3.41},{"text":"You're trying to find out what the man's connections are.","start":3191.78,"stop":3194.698,"duration":2.92}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Wouldn't it --","start":3194.698,"stop":3194.937,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"Robert B. Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me --","start":3194.937,"stop":3195.532,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"-- wouldn't it be justice prejudicial in a civil case to say Mr. Juror or General, ladies and gentlemen of the jury or (Inaudible) stockholders, policy holders of et cetera, the traveler's insurance company?","start":3195.532,"stop":3212.006,"duration":16.47}]},{"speakerName":"Robert B. Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"That is asked on all negligence cases.","start":3212.006,"stop":3214.775,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"As it would be to tell them that that so was to not first have some admission that it is the fact.","start":3214.775,"stop":3224.869,"duration":10.09},{"text":"Can you do it just on your standing?","start":3224.869,"stop":3228.645,"duration":3.78}]},{"speakerName":"Robert B. Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in negligence cases to -- to answer that that is a stock question.","start":3228.645,"stop":3233.953,"duration":5.31},{"text":"We -- we generally can find out from the counsel on the other side the name of his insurance company and we qualify the jury as to that company.","start":3233.953,"stop":3241.844,"duration":7.89}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"And you have that shown in the record before you ask questions, don't you?","start":3241.844,"stop":3246.819,"duration":4.97}]},{"speakerName":"Robert B. Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":3246.819,"stop":3247.273,"duration":0.45},{"text":"Generally, you ask that question privately of the attorney on the other side.","start":3247.273,"stop":3250.161,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes and then have that shown in the record do you not?","start":3250.161,"stop":3252.941,"duration":2.78},{"text":"That he admits that he (Voice Overlap) --","start":3252.941,"stop":3253.914,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Robert B. Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no.","start":3253.914,"stop":3254.668,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"You don't?","start":3254.668,"stop":3255.12,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Robert B. Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":3255.12,"stop":3257.912,"duration":2.79},{"text":"Now, let me -- let me read to the Court the -- the statute under which we examine our -- our jurors.","start":3257.912,"stop":3266.446,"duration":8.53},{"text":"Title 30 of Section 52 of our code provides that in all civil and criminal cases, either parties shall have the right to examine jurors as to their qualifications, interest or bias that would affect the trial of the case and shall have the right under the direction of the Court to examine said jurors as to any matter that might tend to affect their verdict.","start":3266.446,"stop":3287.766,"duration":21.32},{"text":"Now, there seemed to be two -- there seemed to be two different rules and different jurisdiction.","start":3287.766,"stop":3294.14,"duration":6.37},{"text":"Some courts limit questions to what may affect the qualification of a juror.","start":3294.14,"stop":3300.037,"duration":5.9},{"text":"We do not.","start":3300.037,"stop":3301.576,"duration":1.54},{"text":"Our cases say that we may examine on anything that will help determine a man's interest by his prejudice or whatsoever.","start":3301.576,"stop":3310.109,"duration":8.53}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, these questions were asked through the judge.","start":3310.109,"stop":3312.307,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Robert B. Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Through the judge.","start":3312.307,"stop":3312.803,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"He asked this question whether there are members in a --","start":3312.803,"stop":3314.948,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"Robert B. Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"He -- he qualified every juror.","start":3314.948,"stop":3317.853,"duration":2.91},{"text":"That way, they called up in groups of five and qualified generally and the judge does of course.","start":3317.853,"stop":3323.692,"duration":5.84},{"text":"We don't do it ourselves.","start":3323.692,"stop":3326.711,"duration":3.02},{"text":"Now, such type of -- of question has been approved by our courts.","start":3326.711,"stop":3330.614,"duration":3.9},{"text":"The question is briefed.","start":3330.614,"stop":3333.188,"duration":2.57},{"text":"The second and last question is the matter of excluding the public from the trial.","start":3333.188,"stop":3338.709,"duration":5.52},{"text":"We have constitutional and statutory provisions allowing the court and the judge to clear the court in rape cases.","start":3338.709,"stop":3346.092,"duration":7.38},{"text":"That was done in this case, except for the man's families, counsel, the press, his preacher and so forth.","start":3346.092,"stop":3354.324,"duration":8.23},{"text":"Now, that question was before when argued the case last time also and it was very thoroughly briefed and argued.","start":3354.324,"stop":3361.471,"duration":7.15},{"text":"It is briefed this time, but I do not have time to argue.","start":3361.471,"stop":3365.936,"duration":4.47},{"text":"I -- I had hoped to talk a little bit about the facts in this case, but time is -- is running out.","start":3365.936,"stop":3373.776,"duration":7.84}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Can I go back to the jury point a minute?","start":3373.776,"stop":3376.213,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"Robert B. Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3376.213,"stop":3377.095,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Was there a change in your procedures in Alabama between the 1952 motion to quash and 1955 motion to quash?","start":3377.095,"stop":3384.595,"duration":7.5}]},{"speakerName":"Robert B. Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":3384.595,"stop":3385.155,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"None?","start":3385.155,"stop":3385.857,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Robert B. Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":3385.857,"stop":3388.041,"duration":2.18},{"text":"When you say change and preceded, do you mean some kind of statutory change?","start":3388.041,"stop":3390.477,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I mean Mr. Thetford described the procedure, wasn't that obtained in 1952 as well as in 1955?","start":3390.477,"stop":3396.531,"duration":6.05}]},{"speakerName":"Robert B. Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir, it did.","start":3396.531,"stop":3403.333,"duration":6.8}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Billingsley.","start":3403.333,"stop":3404.826,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Orzell Billingsley, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":3404.826,"stop":3408.636,"duration":3.81},{"text":"The case of Jeremiah Reeves versus State of Alabama as reported at 340 U.S. 891, 75 Supreme Court 214 cites two cases in the season of this Court.","start":3408.636,"stop":3431.061,"duration":22.43},{"text":"There was no direction given by this Court and the case was not remanded.","start":3431.061,"stop":3439.738,"duration":8.68},{"text":"As a matter of fact, it's just a reversal and however we take the position that this reversal, unqualified reversal amounted to a plea of not guilty so far as defendant is -- was concerned and that the defendant should have been discharged.","start":3439.738,"stop":3462.278,"duration":22.54},{"text":"We -- this case was decided upon by this Court in December 1954 and the defendant was held in jail until May of 1955 at which time he was again found guilty and sentenced to death.","start":3462.278,"stop":3486.766,"duration":24.49},{"text":"We feel that any discussion of our motions relative to the indictment in the grand jury should have been considered by the Court.","start":3486.766,"stop":3502.586,"duration":15.82},{"text":"On November the 14th as we've already said, the defendant was indicted and he was arraigned on November 15th which I'm sure was less than the indictment -- the arraignment followed the indictment less than 24 hours.","start":3502.586,"stop":3523.631,"duration":21.05},{"text":"The -- the juries of the honorable court of Montgomery has this -- has this discretion to allow the defendant in such cases to withdraw his plea of not guilty and in this case, a plea of not guilty and not guilty by reason of insanity.","start":3523.631,"stop":3545.785,"duration":22.15},{"text":"And it seems to me that where a man is being tried before a court and his life is in jeopardy that it would not have been any trap at all for the Court to allow counsel for the defendant or petitioner to go into the indictment in the grand jury.","start":3545.785,"stop":3569.711,"duration":23.93},{"text":"An interesting thing about the jury commission of Montgomery County is that it is composed of the two Circuit Judges, the sheriff of the County, the judge of the probate court and the clerk of the court.","start":3569.711,"stop":3589.972,"duration":20.26},{"text":"The record will show that the Honorable Judge Carter has been a judge of Montgomery County for 21 years.","start":3589.972,"stop":3602.799,"duration":12.83},{"text":"The record will show that the Honorable Judge Walter B. Jones has been a judge of Montgomery County for 20 years.","start":3602.799,"stop":3613.182,"duration":10.38},{"text":"The record will show that Mr. John R. Mathews who is clerk of the court had been clerk for 20 years.","start":3613.182,"stop":3624.732,"duration":11.55},{"text":"And all during that time, these men have served as jury commissioners.","start":3624.732,"stop":3633.495,"duration":8.76},{"text":"Mr. John R. Mathews is also the Clerk of the jury commission.","start":3633.495,"stop":3640.772,"duration":7.28},{"text":"Montgomery is somewhat different from most of the counties in Alabama and that any qualified citizen might be appointed as a member of the jury commission.","start":3640.772,"stop":3653.211,"duration":12.44},{"text":"But in Montgomery, under the local law, they have to be either judge, sheriff, probate judge, or clerk of the court to be a member of the jury commission.","start":3653.211,"stop":3666,"duration":12.79},{"text":"Now, concerning the fact that these three men mentioned have been commissioners or jury supervisors, whatever you call, for 20 years in a county where the population is 60% white, 40% colored, that they could held during that time very easily to familiarize themselves of the people of that county.","start":3666,"stop":3696.217,"duration":30.22},{"text":"It's different from other counties and that the commissioners might serve a year or two years or whatnot and then they have to come in and adjust themselves to the situation, but we find that even the Honorable Jurist Eugene Carter being asked about the grand juries in Montgomery County.","start":3696.217,"stop":3726.894,"duration":30.68},{"text":"This question is put to him.","start":3726.894,"stop":3730.041,"duration":3.15},{"text":"“Do you know of any occasions when two or more Negroes sit on a grand jury?\"","start":3730.041,"stop":3735.826,"duration":5.78},{"text":"He answers.","start":3735.826,"stop":3737.21,"duration":1.38},{"text":"\"I recall one said.\"","start":3737.21,"stop":3742.981,"duration":5.77},{"text":"He further states on page 55 of the printed record and asked this.","start":3742.981,"stop":3752.771,"duration":9.79},{"text":"Now, the question, “Do you recall the largest number of Negroes you saw serving on a jury at one time?\"","start":3752.771,"stop":3761.002,"duration":8.23},{"text":"Answer: \"No, I wouldn't know.\"","start":3761.002,"stop":3762.951,"duration":1.95},{"text":"Question: \"Have you ever seen as many as four?\"","start":3762.951,"stop":3766.374,"duration":3.42},{"text":"Answer: \"It is impossible for me to tell you as many as four or how many.","start":3766.374,"stop":3772.34,"duration":5.97},{"text":"I don't know; \"We hardly pick a jury now without -- now, listen to this.","start":3772.34,"stop":3778.285,"duration":5.94},{"text":"\"We would hardly pick a jury now about having over four.\"","start":3778.285,"stop":3785.528,"duration":7.24},{"text":"Question:\"Four Negro jurors?\"","start":3785.528,"stop":3787.665,"duration":2.14},{"text":"Answer: \"I remember at one time there were very few.","start":3787.665,"stop":3794.448,"duration":6.78},{"text":"In fact, we were not able to get them until the last year or two.\"","start":3794.448,"stop":3800.883,"duration":6.43},{"text":"Now, this is in 1955 of making.","start":3800.883,"stop":3804.749,"duration":3.87},{"text":"Jeremiah Reeves was indicted on November 14, 1952.","start":3804.749,"stop":3813.852,"duration":9.1},{"text":"That is the mission on the part of the witness here that during that time, they had very few Negroes on the jury list.","start":3813.852,"stop":3828.706,"duration":14.85},{"text":"Now, in 1955, when he's being tried and we asked the Court to let us withdraw the pleas of the defendant and file our motion to quash the indictment, the Court refused.","start":3828.706,"stop":3850.007,"duration":21.3},{"text":"And certainly, it seems that the type of testimony which we have in the case of this kind that there is discrimination or there was in 1952, discrimination in Montgomery County, Alabama.","start":3850.007,"stop":3873.251,"duration":23.24},{"text":"Now, we are not alleging before this Court the proposition as put to you in the respondent's brief on proportional representation.","start":3873.251,"stop":3887.233,"duration":13.98},{"text":"We are not arguing that, but we are saying as your decision -- decisions hold that the selection of jurors should be done according to the Court of Alabama.","start":3887.233,"stop":3905.057,"duration":17.82},{"text":"That is considering all the qualifications out there that they will include men, just men between the ages of 21 and 65.","start":3905.057,"stop":3922.137,"duration":17.08},{"text":"That's all we asked, but the testimony will show that the witnesses in their anxiety to be fair to testify that they deliberately went out and got Negroes and put them on the list.","start":3922.137,"stop":3943.393,"duration":21.26},{"text":"Well, I don't think that is the law either.","start":3943.393,"stop":3946.862,"duration":3.47},{"text":"I don't think it should be a matter of inclusion or exclusion, just a fair system of operation.","start":3946.862,"stop":3956.846,"duration":9.98},{"text":"That's all we asked and in order to try this defendant before their Court.","start":3956.846,"stop":3962.177,"duration":5.33}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You -- does your view -- does your view leave any room for any kind of selective process other than an automatic process of -- I'm not sure I know how that would be.","start":3962.177,"stop":3978.889,"duration":16.71},{"text":"If you have to have a panel of -- of binary of 50, how would you go about getting 50 -- a process that simply involves some kind of selection which is capable of potential -- potentially capable of the exercise of some kind of real bias in New York City or in Montgomery?","start":3978.889,"stop":4014.723,"duration":35.83},{"text":"How would you get 50?","start":4014.723,"stop":4016.283,"duration":1.56},{"text":"Would you -- I suppose you could have a list of -- an alphabetical list of all the male between 21 and 65 in Montgomery and then taking down the line, but sure of that wouldn't -- isn't there necessarily -- does necessarily some selective element in there?","start":4016.283,"stop":4037.819,"duration":21.54}]},{"speakerName":"Orzell Billingsley, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the selective element, Your Honor --","start":4037.819,"stop":4041.106,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not talking about this case, but just generally.","start":4041.106,"stop":4042.999,"duration":1.89},{"text":"Wouldn't --","start":4042.999,"stop":4043.229,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Orzell Billingsley, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, just generally -- just generally, there should be a selective method --","start":4043.229,"stop":4049.472,"duration":6.24}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But it --","start":4049.472,"stop":4049.879,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Orzell Billingsley, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- but it should not be one where you do it in our argument on the basis of race.","start":4049.879,"stop":4055.314,"duration":5.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I couldn't agree with you more.","start":4055.314,"stop":4058.596,"duration":3.28},{"text":"I agree with you as much as you agree with yourself.","start":4058.596,"stop":4060.691,"duration":2.09},{"text":"What I want to know is in selecting people, wouldn't there be some -- wouldn't some question of -- I should think I'm at the brink of the word discretion -- some question of judgment.","start":4060.691,"stop":4075.592,"duration":14.9}]},{"speakerName":"Orzell Billingsley, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":4075.592,"stop":4075.902,"duration":0.31},{"text":"I think that would be --","start":4075.902,"stop":4076.678,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It would have to (Voice Overlap) --","start":4076.678,"stop":4077.585,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Orzell Billingsley, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":4077.585,"stop":4078.306,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- wouldn't it?","start":4078.306,"stop":4078.635,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Orzell Billingsley, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":4078.635,"stop":4079.597,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If you got standard (Inaudible) of people who are fit for the -- for the grand jury, the grand jury service, the determination where the (Inaudible) involved some choice.","start":4079.597,"stop":4091.947,"duration":12.35}]},{"speakerName":"Orzell Billingsley, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":4091.947,"stop":4092.706,"duration":0.76},{"text":"I agree to that and -- and on this (Voice Overlap) --","start":4092.706,"stop":4094.837,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It can't be automatic, can it?","start":4094.837,"stop":4098.285,"duration":3.45}]},{"speakerName":"Orzell Billingsley, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":4098.285,"stop":4098.46,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You can't have an automatic system, except in the way in which I have indicated that you've got a list of everybody in the particular community and then go down the line automatically.","start":4098.46,"stop":4108.343,"duration":9.88}]},{"speakerName":"Orzell Billingsley, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir, but that's -- that's my belief, as a matter of fact, a type of selection which will be a selective method, you might have a grand jury concerned of population in Montgomery County of all Negroes, all white.","start":4108.343,"stop":4126.627,"duration":18.28},{"text":"You may have all Negroes of five or six.","start":4126.627,"stop":4129.906,"duration":3.28},{"text":"But now, this is a pretty peculiar situation that even the Solicitor on cross-examination, I asked him about the grand jury which indicted Jeremiah Reeves.","start":4129.906,"stop":4144.209,"duration":14.3},{"text":"I asked him, question: \"Were there any Negroes on the grand jury that indicted Jeremiah Reeves, Jr.?\"","start":4144.209,"stop":4151.238,"duration":7.03},{"text":"He answers, “I do not know for sure.","start":4151.238,"stop":4154.934,"duration":3.7},{"text":"My best judgment states, I wouldn't know.","start":4154.934,"stop":4158.223,"duration":3.29},{"text":"My best judgment would be no.","start":4158.223,"stop":4161.412,"duration":3.19},{"text":"It will be no.”","start":4161.412,"stop":4163.187,"duration":1.77},{"text":"Now, it is -- it -- it could be peculiar for you have 18 men on the grand jury and all of them are white men.","start":4163.187,"stop":4175.937,"duration":12.75},{"text":"Every one of them is white men.","start":4175.937,"stop":4177.966,"duration":2.03},{"text":"Now, that could happen, but it's peculiar.","start":4177.966,"stop":4181.546,"duration":3.58},{"text":"It makes me suspicious.","start":4181.546,"stop":4185.779,"duration":4.23},{"text":"I just -- I can't explain it.","start":4185.779,"stop":4192.522,"duration":6.74}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Does -- does your jury requirement include literacy?","start":4192.522,"stop":4200.509,"duration":7.99}]},{"speakerName":"Orzell Billingsley, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":4200.509,"stop":4201.969,"duration":1.46},{"text":"It does.","start":4201.969,"stop":4203.531,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if you had -- if you had a community -- I'm not saying Montgomery of course.","start":4203.531,"stop":4208.986,"duration":5.45},{"text":"If you had a community in which for one reason or another, there was a portion of the population although citizens predominantly couldn't write.","start":4208.986,"stop":4222.302,"duration":13.32},{"text":"We have known countries that are now in some foreign countries like India in which I don't know what the percentage of literacy there the other day.","start":4222.302,"stop":4232.358,"duration":10.06},{"text":"It's rapidly being cut down in literacy.","start":4232.358,"stop":4236.848,"duration":4.49},{"text":"You might get a situation where an allowable standard of selection would exclude a certain group.","start":4236.848,"stop":4247.169,"duration":10.32},{"text":"Wouldn't it?","start":4247.169,"stop":4247.61,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Orzell Billingsley, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":4247.61,"stop":4249.027,"duration":1.42},{"text":"It -- it possibly would.Of course in Montgomery County, it's different from most of the county.","start":4249.027,"stop":4254.716,"duration":5.69},{"text":"You have a highly intelligent --","start":4254.716,"stop":4256.495,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but I --","start":4256.495,"stop":4257.386,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Orzell Billingsley, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- selection of Negroes in that county.","start":4257.386,"stop":4259.205,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But, I'm not -- it's remote to mean to suggest not (Voice Overlap) --","start":4259.205,"stop":4262.553,"duration":3.35}]},{"speakerName":"Orzell Billingsley, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":4262.553,"stop":4263.302,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But I was thinking of Judge Carter with the interesting statement about the change that is taking place to meet the gratifying things to read that, I hope.","start":4263.302,"stop":4273.614,"duration":10.31}]},{"speakerName":"Orzell Billingsley, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir, but the change --","start":4273.614,"stop":4274.431,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- impliedly that if he said there are good to offer and bad to offer, good wives and bad wives, so he could say also good husband and bad husband.","start":4274.431,"stop":4282.664,"duration":8.23}]},{"speakerName":"Orzell Billingsley, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":4282.664,"stop":4283.872,"duration":1.21},{"text":"Well, it seems that's referred to by the Honorable Judge Carter that is also gratifying to me, but the change referred to by him came about after Jeremiah Reeves was arraigned and indicted and convicted.","start":4283.872,"stop":4301.647,"duration":17.77},{"text":"And of course, our -- our question that changed according to the evidence.","start":4301.647,"stop":4309.092,"duration":7.44},{"text":"Our time is short and I would like to make just one statement concerning the demurrers made by the Solicitor in this case regarding the NAACP.","start":4309.092,"stop":4318.414,"duration":9.32},{"text":"I think it -- it tended to prejudice the minds of the jurors or as far as the statement is concerned in which he mentioned that this case was being financed by the NAACP.","start":4318.414,"stop":4336.074,"duration":17.66},{"text":"He could have easily asked me and I would have told him who spend for the case of Jeremiah Reeves, but I think we know very well the status of the NAACP in the State of Alabama, cases before you now of the case of NAACP, but we submit that this case should be reversed (Inaudible).","start":4336.074,"stop":4363.244,"duration":27.17}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Jan  8 - 9, 1958","petitioner":"Reeves","respondent":"Alabama","docket":"66","citation":"355 US 368 (1958)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/355/368","lowerCourt":"","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Jan 13, 1958"}